Title: Add Transformation Tree Getter to Controller API
Body:
**Description**  Add controller API support to read TF tree of the robot.    **Related Issues**  Closes #1603    **Tasks**    - [x] Create `tf_tree_print()` to debug the results    - [ ] Read transformation tree in `WbRobot.cpp`      - [x] Find and send relevant primitives (joints and links) in the robot tree      - [x] Rotation and translation in respect to the parent node      - [x] Store relevant HingeJointParameters       - [x] Add support for different joint implementations. Find solid endpoints and continue parsing the tree.        - [x] WbSliderJoint        - [x] WbHingeJoint2        - [x] BallJoint        - [x] WbHingeJoint      - [x] Compress the tf (we don't care about link<->link  only device<->joint)      - [ ] Verify if there are relevant and unhandled nodes (if it works for e-puck doesn't mean it will work for the other robots)    - [x] Add API for controller      - [x] Parse the transformation tree      - [x] Expose getter function      - [x] Clean the tree      - [x] Add Python support to be able to test it with `webots_ros2`    - [ ] Add support for languages other than C    - [ ] Add documentation    - [ ] Add unit tests    - [x] Shift origin of joint in case the parent is node is considered irrelevant    - [ ] Test      - [x] WbHingeJoint      - [ ] WbHingeJoint2      - [ ] BallJoint      - [ ] WbSliderJoint    **Additional context**    <details><summary>Controller for the tree printing and visualization (.dot)</summary>    ```c  #include <stdio.h>  #include <webots/robot.h>    #define TIME_STEP 64    static void tf_make_dot_rec(FILE *f  WbTransformNodeObject *root) {    // Generate .dot file. You can visualize it later as:    // $ dot -Tpng /tmp/robot.dot > /tmp/robot.png && xdg-open /tmp/robot.png    for (int i = 0; i < root->n_children; i++) {      fprintf(f  "%d -> %d;
"  root->id  root->children[i]->id);      if (root->children[i]->type == WB_TF_NODE_LINK)        fprintf(f  "%d [shape=box];
"  root->children[i]->id);      tf_make_dot_rec(f  root->children[i]);    }  }    static void tf_make_dot(WbTransformNodeObject *root) {    FILE *f;    f = fopen("/tmp/robot.dot"  "w");    fprintf(f  "digraph graphname {
");    fprintf(f  "%d [shape=box];
"  root->id);    tf_make_dot_rec(f  root);    fprintf(f  "}
");    fclose(f);  }    static void tf_print_details(WbTransformNodeObject *root) {    if (root->type == WB_TF_NODE_LINK) {      if (root->parent == NULL)        printf("From root node to [%d] %s
"  root->id  root->name);      else        printf("From [%d] %s to [%d] %s
"  (root->parent)->id  (root->parent)->name  root->id  root->name);      printf("Rotation matrix = [
");      printf("  %f %f %f
"  root->rotation[0]  root->rotation[1]  root->rotation[2]);      printf("  %f %f %f
"  root->rotation[3]  root->rotation[4]  root->rotation[5]);      printf("  %f %f %f
"  root->rotation[6]  root->rotation[7]  root->rotation[8]);      printf("]
");      printf("Translation = [ %f %f %f ]
"  root->translation[0]  root->translation[1]  root->translation[2]);      printf("
");    }      for (int i = 0; i < root->n_children; i++)      tf_print_details(root->children[i]);  }    static void tf_tree_print(WbTransformNodeObject *root  int level) {    for (int i = 0; i < level; i++)      printf("      |");    if (root->type == WB_TF_NODE_JOINT)      printf("----(%d)
"  root->id);    else      printf("----[%d] %s
"  root->id  root->name);        for (int i = 0; i < root->n_children; i++)      tf_tree_print(root->children[i]  level+1);  }    int main(int argc  char *argv[]) {    wb_robot_init();      wb_robot_step(TIME_STEP);    WbTransformNodeObject* tf_tree = wb_robot_get_transform_tree();      tf_tree_print(tf_tree  0);    tf_print_details(tf_tree);    tf_make_dot(tf_tree);      wb_robot_cleanup();    return 0;  }  ```  </details>      <details><summary>Verification controller in Python</summary>    ```py  from controller import Robot      def tf_print_details(root):      if root.get_type() == Robot.TF_NODE_LINK:          if not root.get_parent():              print(f'From root node to [{root.get_id()}] {root.get_name()}')          else:              print(f'From [{root.get_id()}] {root.get_name()} to [{root.get_parent().get_id()}] {root.get_parent().get_name()}')          print('Rotation matrix = [')          print(f'  {root.get_rotation()[0]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[1]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[2]:.3f}')          print(f'  {root.get_rotation()[3]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[4]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[5]:.3f}')          print(f'  {root.get_rotation()[6]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[7]:.3f} {root.get_rotation()[8]:.3f}')          print(']')          print(f'Translation = [ {root.get_translation()[0]:.3f} {root.get_translation()[1]:.3f} {root.get_translation()[2]:.3f} ]')          print('')        for child in root.get_children():          tf_print_details(child)      robot = Robot()    timestep = int(robot.getBasicTimeStep())  robot.step(timestep)  tree = robot.getTransformTree()  tf_print_details(tree)  ```  </details>

Title: Fixed Webots Windows launcher to escape properly spaces in arguments
Body: A user reported on Discord that he was unable to open a world file that includes spaces in the path when starting Webots from a Windows DOS console. He tried several things  including adding double quotes around the world path  but that didn't work. I found that adding 3 double quotes around the world path worked  but is quite odd:  ```dos  C:\Users\Olivier>"C:\Program Files\Webots\msys64\mingw64\bin\webots.exe" """C:\Program Files\Webots\projects\samples\devices\worlds\camera.wbt"""  ```   This PR fixes the problem and makes that adding a single double quote around the path is sufficient  as it should be:  ```dos  C:\Users\Olivier>"C:\Program Files\Webots\msys64\mingw64\bin\webots.exe" "C:\Program Files\Webots\projects\samples\devices\worlds\camera.wbt"  ```

Title: Add no rendering flag
Body: **Description**  This PR adds `--no-rendering` which hides 3D view.    **Related Issues**  Implements #2245    **Tasks**    - [x] Basic implementation    - [x] Full implementation      - [x] Configuration should be read/written to file      - [x] Configuration should be accessible through `--no-rendering` flag      - [x] Buttons in play menu      - [x] Menu bar        - [x] Simulation > Show/Hide        - [x] View > Scene Interactions > Disable 3D View      - [x] <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>4</kbd>      - [x] Supervisor API       - [x] Movie recording shortcuts    - [x] Add GUI icon      - [x] Improve icon resolution and shape     - [x] Implement backward compatibility strategy      - [x] Command line      - [ ] Supervisor (this will fail  open for discussion)      - [x] From file    - [x] Add to changelog    - [x] Change documentation    **New behavior**    - Case A    - before `webots --mode=run`    - now `webots --mode=fast`  - Case B    - before `webots --mode=fast`    - now `webots --mode=fast --no-rendering`  - Case C    - before you want to use mode `realtime` without 3D view (you cannot)    - now `webots --mode=realtime --no-rendering`  - Case D    - before <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>4</kbd> to start fast mode    - now <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>3</kbd> to enable new fast mode and <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>4</kbd> to toggle 3D view  - Case E    - before `wb_supervisor_simulation_get_mode()` returns `WB_SUPERVISOR_SIMULATION_MODE_RUN` or `WB_SUPERVISOR_SIMULATION_MODE_FAST`    - now `wb_supervisor_simulation_get_mode()` returns only `WB_SUPERVISOR_SIMULATION_MODE_FAST`    **Backward incompatible**  - `webots --mode=run`    - deprecation warning + falling back to `fast` mode  - `WB_SUPERVISOR_SIMULATION_MODE_RUN` from Supervisoir API is deleted

Title: Fix Supervisor API field operations
Body: Address #2292.    The `wb_supervisor_field_get_*` functions return inconsistent values during the same controller step if a previous `wb_supervisor_field_set_*` instructions is called:  * it returns the correct updated value before the set instruction(s) are sent to Webots  * it returns the old value after the set instruction(s) are sent to Webots and are no longer stored on the controller side    It is well [documented](https://www.cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/supervisor#wb_supervisor_field_set_sf_bool) that values could be wrong  but it is very unclear for users why sometimes they are correct and sometimes not.    In this PR I tried to fix this behavior by keeping as long as possible the set operation list on the controller side and send it to Webots only if another field operation is requested ensuring that the set operations are applied before the other field operation.    Improved documentation:  https://www.cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/supervisor?version=fix-supervisor-field-operations#wb_supervisor_field_set_sf_bool

Title: Fix active loop waiting for extern controllers
Body: Fix #2253: Webots uses too many computer resources when waiting for extern controllers (especially in run/fast mode).    This fix consists in pausing the timer that triggers the ``WbControlledWorld::step()`` if Webots is waiting for an extern controller and restart the timer when an extern controller connects.  This way the step function is not continuously called and aborted.    Another change of this PR is that a user clicks on the step button while waiting for an extern controller first connection  the step request is ignored and the step button is not grayed out (see  #2284).  This could be more intuitive and we could even print a warning in the console explaining that Webots is waiting for an extern controller.

Title: Add URDF base_footprint link
Body: **Description**  Turtlebot3 and Husky have `base_footprint` link as a parent:  https://github.com/husky/husky/blob/4647d303365b17ccb455f4345bd14320f49f1134/husky_description/urdf/husky.urdf.xacro#L95  https://github.com/ROBOTIS-GIT/turtlebot3/blob/41e43d4a10aada68b8a7d05675550550091586d6/turtlebot3_description/urdf/turtlebot3_burger.urdf#L47  Probably  it is similar to the other robots as well.    This is important because some packages depend on `base_footprint` link  e.g. `turtlebot3_navigation2`:  https://github.com/ROBOTIS-GIT/turtlebot3/blob/41e43d4a10aada68b8a7d05675550550091586d6/turtlebot3_navigation2/param/burger.yaml#L9    Usually  this can be changed by overriding configuration or by adding static transform in a launch file. However  this may be a cleaner solution and closer to what the community has been doing.    **Related Issues**  https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros2/pull/110    **Tasks**    - [x] Add `base_footprint` link    - [x] Update tests

Title: Get point cloud as a buffer
Body: **Description**  Since I couldn't find a solution to improve the performance of `getPointCloud()` without changing the API (see #2296) this introduces a new argument `dtype` which defines data type.    See conversation:  https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros2/pull/148#issuecomment-702001390    **Related Issues**  Closes #2283    **Tasks**   - [x] Add to changelog   - [x] Add documentation    **API Proposal**    `getPointCloud([dtype])`  - `dtype` can be ['list'  'buffer']    **Additional context**  - If `dtype` == 'list'    - Creating a list is 50-60% faster than the previous implementation  - If `dtype` == 'buffer'    - Performances are almost the same as for C API    - Data can be passed directly to [`PointCloud2`](http://docs.ros.org/melodic/api/sensor_msgs/html/msg/PointCloud2.html) (see [example](https://gist.github.com/pgorczak/5c717baa44479fa064eb8d33ea4587e0))    - It can be converted to numpy array using `data = np.frombuffer(data  dtype=np.uint8)` without overhead  - This change doesn't break the API  - It can scale to other parts of the API without breaking it  - We can continue adding new data types      ----      **Personal notes:**    - Constructor for `array.array` (`newarrayobject`):  https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/e51dd9dad6590bf3a940723fbbaaf4f64a3c9228/Modules/arraymodule.c#L570    - Creates `array.array` object by calling `array_array_frombytes`:  https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/e51dd9dad6590bf3a940723fbbaaf4f64a3c9228/Modules/arraymodule.c#L2663    - Bytes to `array.array` is only doing `memcpy()` (and some checks):  https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/e51dd9dad6590bf3a940723fbbaaf4f64a3c9228/Modules/arraymodule.c#L1615    - Access to memory without copying (only get):  ```Python  mv = memoryview(data)  mv[0:100]  ```    - Pointer to the memory of `array.array`:  ```C  op->ob_item  ```    - The internal buffer cannot be alternated through [`PyObject_GetBuffer`](https://docs.python.org/3/c-api/buffer.html#c.PyObject_GetBuffer) as `view->buf` is assigned on the call:  https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/e51dd9dad6590bf3a940723fbbaaf4f64a3c9228/Modules/arraymodule.c#L2523    -

Title: Get quaternion from InertialUnit
Body: This PR adds support to the `InertialUnit` node that allows retrieval of quaternions. This allows us to avoid gimbal-lock and to be closer to the real sensor implementation. It also fixes orientation in ROS.    **Physical Sensor Example**  I used an MPU6050 sensor (driver implementation) as an example:  - quaternions are directly returned from the sensor: https://github.com/ElectronicCats/mpu6050/blob/845ee3978b6554967e510d8dd5f74c2c764908e3/src/MPU6050_6Axis_MotionApps20.h#L438  - roll/pitch/yaw are computed from the quaternions: https://github.com/ElectronicCats/mpu6050/blob/845ee3978b6554967e510d8dd5f74c2c764908e3/src/MPU6050_6Axis_MotionApps20.h#L547  - gimbal-lock issue: https://github.com/ElectronicCats/mpu6050/blob/845ee3978b6554967e510d8dd5f74c2c764908e3/examples/MPU6050_DMP6_ESPWiFi/MPU6050_DMP6_ESPWiFi.ino#L103    **Non-related fixes**  - PointStamped is published by GPS instead of Point. This also fixes ROS tests.    **Documentation**  https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/inertialunit?version=feature-inertial-unit-quaternion    **ROS Objective**  The ROS layer should be changed  so RVIz and Webots orientation match if the coordinate system is ENU:  ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2135826/97864165-77b18a80-1d08-11eb-86ab-d0b3aa8ea41f.png)    **Related Issues**  https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros/issues/37  https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros/pull/38/    **Tasks**    - [x] Basic implementation    - [x] Decide on how the lookup table should be implemented    - [x] Add getter for `noise` parameter    - [x] Python/Java/Matlab    - [x] Documentation    - [x] Document gimbal-lock case    - [x] Changelog

Title: Add recognition and segmentation functionalities to default robot window
Body: Address #2400: add checkboxed in the Camera tab of the default robot window to enabled/disable recognition and segmentation functionalities.  These checkboxes are displayed only if the `Recognition` node is available  respectively `Recognition.segmentation` field is set to TRUE.    ![Screenshot from 2020-11-04 13-03-40](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5910449/98109668-38b53d80-1e9e-11eb-82b6-c3915843f9bf.png)      Tasks:  * [x] add Camera API function `wb_camera_recognition_is_segmentation_enabled` to check if the segmentation has been enabled from the controller or not: this is needed to update the checkbox in the robot window  * [x] add checkboxes and related code to show the recognition and segmentation status and update it when changed from the  controller  * [x] fix internal status of segmentation enabled/disabled in the libController that was not matching Webots after disabling the camera recognition functionality    The `wb_camera_recognition_is_segmentation_enabled` C API function is needed internally.  We can decide if we want to make it public  documented and available on all the APIs or if we want to keep it private and move it in a `camera_private.h` header file.

Title: Make Lidar return INF if depth is out of range
Body: **Description**  Previously  the LiDAR would return MAX_RANGE if the depth is out-of-range. The behavior is hard to handle in robotic applications as we don't know whether the depth is equal to MAX_RANGE (consider the noise as well) or the depth is out-of-range.    **Analysis of the similar systems**    LDS-01  It seems it doesn't return measurements at all indices  https://github.com/ROBOTIS-GIT/hls_lfcd_lds_driver/blob/master/src/hlds_laser_publisher.cpp#L110  This probably depends on the measurement quality or range. I have this LiDAR in Lausanne so that I can verify - documentation is poor.    XV-11  It has very detailed information about each measurement  https://github.com/memristor/avr-lidar/blob/master/src/xv11.c#L99  https://github.com/rohbotics/xv_11_laser_driver/blob/kinetic-devel/src/xv11_laser.cpp#L93    More expensive LiDARs like Hokuyo URG also give information if an object is too close or too far:  https://www.roscomponents.com/en/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=49    Gazebo returns infinity if the object above or below the range.    **Related Issues**  Fixes #1985    **Tasks**    - [x] Implement fix    - [x] Add to changelog    - [x] Add to documentation    - [x] Verify whether the noise is added to INF    **Result**  Note: infinity values are not visualized.    ![Peek 2020-12-08 20-36](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2135826/101534272-33647a80-3997-11eb-987b-ddef1976fee2.gif)  **before**: besides improper handling of invalid values  notice there are some artifacts as well    ![Peek 2020-12-08 20-50](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2135826/101534298-39f2f200-3997-11eb-95f9-c854b66f50a9.gif)  **now**

Title: Rework of external force torque logic
Body: **Related Issues**  This pull-request relates to issue #358    **Description**  As suggested in issue #358  if an external force is applied to a node without physics (typically a sensor which by default don't)  and a node ancestor with physics exists  then it should be possible to apply the external force anyway.    The proposed solution goes up the chain until it finds a dynamic solid and does fix issue #358.    Currently  **it searches upwards  not sideways ** so if there's a Transform or a Group with multiple children (some with and some without physics)  applying a force on a children wouldn't actually move the entire Group. (Like the stacked box/cylinder on the video)    The search can be extended sideways too  but in practice I don't really know if it's desirable because:  - If the Group/Transform is part of a Robot  then by the Physics rules (i.e _if any of the children nodes have physics  then the topmost node (the Robot) also needs to_)  so searching upwards will always lead to a solid with physics to be found.  - If it's not part of a Robot  it means it's part of the environment and likely was _intended_ to have parts with physics and parts without  would it make sense for everything to be affected by the force? (assuming there's an ancestor with physics  otherwise can't be moved anyway)    Which begs the question if it's even necessary to search at all since we can go straight to the Robot node and test that one.   The only reason for actually climbing the hierarchy that I can imagine is if it's desirable to apply the force as close to the cursor as possible. In which case an even more deep search should be done  in all directions  and shouldn't just involve node vicinity (with transforms it could very well not be physically near  despite being close node-wise). In short  reverting to the Robot node might be the more 'reasonable' option.    Basically  I don't know if the proposed solution is sufficient  or even overkill.    **Test world**  [force_logic.zip](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/files/5780206/force_logic.zip)    **Video**    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/103865457-87609d00-50c4-11eb-82cb-9e3aa13fed37.mp4    Red have physics  green don't. The Stack behind is a Transform composed by a Box + Cylinder    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/103865488-92b3c880-50c4-11eb-83e9-ffab10ea300b.mp4

Title: Improve webots server caching
Body: **Description**  Webots does no check to verify if a streaming-viewer client already has an image in its cache or not.    To fix that  I implemented a simple etag mecanism.  - When webots send a file  it put the hash off the image in the etag header.  - If a browser want to query again webots about a file  it will put the hash from the etag field in the "If-None-Match" header. (this is done automatically by the browser)  - When receiving a query about a file  webots will check if their is a "If-None-Match" header and compare its content with the hash of the requested file. If the two hashes are the same  webots will answer with a 304 Not modified and not transfer the file again.    I implemented it by hand because I did not find such an preexisting option in Qt.

Title: Implement node state list
Body: We want to add two supervisor functions:  - `wb_supervisor_node_save_state(node  state_name)`: saves node's state (like translation  rotation...) and all children of the node with name `state_name` (string)  - `wb_supervisor_node_load_state(node  state_name)` loads node's state (like translation  rotation...) and all children of the node with name `state_name` (string)    This will allow a partial restart of the world  allowing us to run multiple reinforcement learning environments in a single instance of Webots.    This PR also fixes #2759    **Documentation**  https://www.cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/supervisor?version=feature-state-list#wb_supervisor_node_save_state    https://www.cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/supervisor?version=feature-state-list#resetreload-matrix    **Tasks**  - [x] Add  `state_name` to `WbNode::reset` and `WbNode::save`  - [x] Add Supervisor C from controller import Supervisor    robot = Supervisor()  timestep = int(robot.getBasicTimeStep())    left_motor = robot.getDevice('left wheel motor')  right_motor = robot.getDevice('right wheel motor')  left_motor.setPosition(float('inf'))  right_motor.setPosition(float('inf'))  left_motor.setVelocity(2)  right_motor.setVelocity(2)      target_node = robot.getFromDef('TARGET_NODE')  for _ in range(50): robot.step(timestep)  target_node.saveState('my_state')  time.sleep(0.5)    for _ in range(50): robot.step(timestep)  target_node.saveState('my_state2')  time.sleep(0.5)    for _ in range(50): robot.step(timestep)  target_node.loadState('my_state2')  robot.step(timestep)  time.sleep(0.5)    left_motor.setPosition(float('inf'))  right_motor.setPosition(float('inf')) Title: TransmissionJoint specifications
Body: Proposition for the specifications of the `TransmissionJoint`:    `TransmissionJoint` derived from `HingeJoint`    ```  TransmissionJoint {    field SFNode  jointParameters2  NULL   # { HingeJointParameters  PROTO } (driven side)  required    field SFFloat backlash          0      # (-inf  inf)    field SFFloat multiplier        1      # (-inf  inf)  required    field SFNode startPoint         NULL   # {Solid  Slot  PROTO}  }  ```    for **classic gear**:  - the axis of jointParameters and jointParameters2 should match.  - multiplier should be negative    from ODE standpoint  nothing special  we can feed the multiplier as a ratio directly.    for **chain drive**:    - the axis of jointParameters and jointParameters2 should match.  - multiplier should be positive    from ODE standpoint  chain drive transmission requires the radii of the two wheels so in practice we impose: `radius1 = 1` and `radius2 = multiplier`.    for **bevel gears**:  - the axis of jointParameters and jointParameters2 should differ.  - ~~the multiplier should be negative.~~    ODE doesn't have a way of specifying the ratio for bevel gears  it's inferred from the provided axis.    Implementation notes:   - the two axis must intersect  show warning otherwise. ODE accepts it anyway but the results are meaningless.  - bevel gear is consistent with how it's defined in ODE  but not ideal from a user perspective as the multiplier is inferred from the axis. So webots documentation should clarify how the multiplier is inferred under the hood and that the provided value isn't being enforced. As it stands  this type of joint wouldn't be easy to use in practice.

Title: replace rgb16f by rgba16f in order to be compatible with webgl
Body: **Description**  In WebGL2  the RGB16F format is not color-renderable whereas the RGBA16F format is (https://www.khronos.org/registry/webgl/extensions/EXT_color_buffer_half_float/). I propose to replace RGB16F by RGBA16F is these two functions that I need in WebGl.

Title: Modify shaders to have float in the form 1 0 and not just 1
Body: **Description**  WebGL does not accept shaders where a float has the form 1 or 0 (instead of 1.0 and 0.0).     I changed the float in some shaders in order for them to be compatible with WebGL

Title: Fix padding of vec3 for std140
Body: **Description**  Wren uses the size of the struct Lights to initialize the corresponding uniform buffer.  In the shaders  we redeclare this struct with the std140 layer.    However  std140 always rounds up to size of vec4 (16 bytes) but we have a vec3 (12 bytes) in the struct. (https://www.khronos.org/opengl/wiki/Interface_Block_(GLSL)#Memory_layout)    So the sizeof is short of 4 bytes compared to the size expected by GLSL.

Title: Fix the type of GL_R16f GLRGB16f and GL_RGBA16f in GlFormatParams
Body: **Description**  The type corresponding to WR_TEXTURE_INTERNAL_FORMAT_R16F  WR_TEXTURE_INTERNAL_FORMAT_RGB16F and WR_TEXTURE_INTERNAL_FORMAT_RGBA16F is currently GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE.    However  according to the documentation of opengl (https://www.khronos.org/registry/OpenGL-Refpages/gl4/html/glTexImage2D.xhtml) and webgl (https://www.khronos.org/registry/webgl/specs/latest/2.0/#TEXTURE_TYPES_FORMATS_FROM_DOM_ELEMENTS_TABLE) it should be GL_HALF_FLOAT (or GL_FLOAT).    Webgl does not work if the type is set to GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE.

Title: modify shaders to have float in the form x 0
Body: WebGL does not accept shaders where a float has the form 6 instead of 6.0    I changed the floats in some shaders in order for them to be compatible with WebGL

Title: Robotino3 proto is modified to increase movement speed and accuracy and change orientation to FLU
Body: Robotino3 is modified to be able to move fast (was very slow). Changed robot's coordinate system to x=forward y=left z=up.    proto/Robotino3.proto:  * changed robots coordinate system to x=front  y=left  z=up  * corrected position of wheels  * robot > Physics > centerOfMass 0 0 -0.1    proto/Robotino3Wheel.proto:  * device > RotationalMotor > maxVelocity 137.46 (allows max. speed 10 m/s forwards)  * boundingObject > Cylinder > height 0.01  (from 0.06  better robot rotation)    controller/robotino3.c  base.c  base.h:  * increased max speed from 0.1 m/s to 8 m/s  * increased demo movement speed from 0.05 m/s to 2 m/s  * corrected the movement calculation  * added acceleration    worlds/robotino3.wbt:      WorldInfo > ContactProperties >        material1 "WheelMat"        coulombFriction 0 2 0        bounce 0    (frictionRotation and forceDependentSlip have been removed)    https://cyberbotics.com/doc/guide/robotino3 should be changed to this new ContactProperties too.    ONLY USE IN WORLDS WITH WorldInfo.coordinateSystem "NUE"  (maybe the physics engine has an error in asymmetric friction with "ENU")

Title: Significantly simplify the usage of the ros controller
Body: This PR significantly simplifies the usage of the `ros` controller:  - Integrates `ros_control` (the `--use-ros-control` flag) to allow usage of a differential drive  joint state publisher  trajectory follower  and other controllers.  - Adds the `--auto-publish` flag that automatically enables all sensors and creates necessary topics.  - Adds the `robot_description` ROS param which contains the robot's URDF (necessary for many ROS packages).    **Impact**  Take [the Pioneer controller](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros/blob/master/src/pioneer3at.cpp) from the `webots_ros` package as an example. The controller with over 300 lines of code is not needed anymore. Furthermore  to simplify the controller  we "cheated" by calculating odometry from GPS and IMU. There is no way something like that would work in the real world. The odometry is now calculated from the wheel encoders.    **Tasks**  - [x] Proof of concept  - [x] Test with differential drive    - [x] We need `robot_state_publisher` here. `Robot description couldn't be retrieved from param server.`   - [ ] ~~Test with MoveIt~~ (I think it is better to finish this in another PR)  - [x] Rethink namespaces (e.g. `/robot_description`  URDF prefix...)  - [x] Document  - [x] Changelog     **Useful commands**  ```bash  rosrun controller_manager controller_manager list  ```

Title: Fix load order in the ros controller

Title: Fix update of supervisor field count
Body: Fix #1519: notify the supervisor controllers when the size of a MF field that is cached changed so that the size in the libController can be updated.    _Changes to existing messages_  Previously the MF field count was correctly updated only for MFNode fields when a node was removed.  To avoid duplicating the update  I changed the `C_SUPERVISOR_NODE_REMOVE_NODE` message so that it just deletes any cached instance of the deleted node. But the field count will be updated using the new `C_SUPERVISOR_FIELD_COUNT_CHANGED` messsage.  Similarly  when importing a node from a supervisor  Webots returned immediately the number of imported nodes to update the cached field count. For MFNode fields this return message has been removed and replaced by the new `C_SUPERVISOR_FIELD_COUNT_CHANGED`.

Title: HingeJointWithBacklash proto to model effect of backlash
Body: **EDIT: This information is outdated  see comments below.**    # Specifications   For the purpose of modeling mechanical backlash in Webots  in #2756 the option to introduce ODE's transmission joint was considered but this approach suffers from some drawbacks. Most notably  as it relies on the contact between the two wheels to  transmit the torque  deviations between input and output are introduced due to the effect of CFM at the transmission level  and these errors accumulate over time which makes this approach undesirable for the current objective.    The second more promising approach is to model backlash by extending the HingeJoint class and relying on minStop maxStop to achieve the desired effect.     ```  HingeJoint {    # current fields    field MFNode  device            [ ]   # {RotationalMotor  PositionSensor  Brake  PROTO}    field SFFloat position          0     # [0  inf)    # added fields      field SFFloat backlash          0     # [0  inf)    field SFFloat gearMass          0     # [0  inf)    field SFNode  startPoint        NULL  # {Transform} it's only for visualizing the gear  }  ```    # Preliminary result  The following videos show the results that can be obtained using the proposed approach and are obtained by cascading two HingeJoints. In **red** is shown the behavior of a classic HingeJoint (with no backlash) whereas in **blue** the case with a very large (0.2) backlash  just to make things more evident. Both motors are given the same command.    No backlash  both pendulums (single hinge and cascaded hinge) behave the same    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/109315387-c69ca600-784a-11eb-9f55-1d27f9743138.mp4    Without any gravity:    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/109310957-7707ab80-7845-11eb-9d8b-be487de20f62.mp4    With gravity:    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/109311012-8a1a7b80-7845-11eb-8b38-72ca8889ebb6.mp4

Title: Calibrated Robocup ball
Body: # Description  The Robocup ball was calibrated according to the following measurements:    ## Damping  We recorded a shoot:    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1264964/111494285-a02da480-873e-11eb-882c-bbc9e3d28330.mp4    The length of the artificial grass is 1.07 m.  The initial velocity of the ball (computed on the first two frames) is 0.841 m/s.  The distance traveled is (computed) 0.621 m.  When testing in Webots  we applied a force of 3.28 N at the top of the ball  so that the initial velocity was 0.84 m/s.  The distance traveled by the simulated ball was 0.62 m.    ## Bounce  We dropped the ball from 2 m on the artificial grass and it bounced up to about 0.5 m.  The bounce parameter in the simulation was adjusted so that when dropping the ball from 2 m  it bounced up to about 0.5 m.

Title: Darwin op expose backlash
Body: **Description**  This PR exposes a `backlash` field and activates backlash on all joints (amount: 0.04) for the `HingeJoint` based Darwin-OP (the default one).    It should be noted that:    -  The `HingeJointWithBacklash` PROTO already has a mechanism that reverts to a simple `HingeJoint` in case backlash is 0. So in theory there should be no performance difference between the original Darwin and the modified version if backlash is enforced to 0 (condition for it to revert). In practice however there appears to be some overhead in the latter case which makes it more computationally complex  which is why in this PR the switch is done directly in the Darwin PROTO despite this mechanism existing in the `HingeJointWithBacklash`.    **Performance metrics**  Scenario:    - 8 robots walking straight  - timestep 8 [ms]  - run on a (old) laptop (Geforce GT 730M). (Threads = 1  shadows disables  AA disabled)  - 2000 steps    World metrics:  |                            | solids | joints | geometries |  |----------------------------|--------|--------|------------|  | HingeJ (backlash = false)  | 265    | 160    | 305        |  | HingeJWB (backlash = 0)    | 265    | 160    | 305        |  | HingeJWB (backlash = 0.04) | 425    | 320    | 305        |    Performance:  |                            | prePhysics(ms) | physics(ms)     | postPhysics(ms) | mainRendering(ms) |  |----------------------------|----------------|-----------------|-----------------|-------------------|  | HingeJ (backlash = false)  | 655 [0.328]    | 31588 [15.794]  | 6000 [3.000]    | 10048 [5.024]     |  | HingeJWB (backlash = 0)    | 741 [0.371]    | 31766 [15.883]  | 7212 [3.606]    | 9615 [4.796]      |  | HingeJWB (backlash = 0.04) | 1193 [0.597]   | 180843 [90.422] | 13639 [6.820]   | 8609 [4.294]      |    It was obtained using the `--log-performance` argument. The values represent: TOTAL [AVG].

Title: Fix incorrect stopCFM and stopERP imposition when world uses non default global CFM ERP
Body: **Description**  The current version loads user-defined `stopERP` and `stopCFM` correctly and also handles invalid values. However  if the world being loaded uses non-default values for global `ERP` and `CFM` (i.e not 0.2 and 1e-5)  then in [this](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/e80fb802139d4645eed30f9865017a742607c185/src/webots/nodes/WbHingeJoint.cpp#L142) line the `stopERP` and `stopCFM` actually being imposed on the joint are the default ones defined in `HingeJointParameters` [here](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/e80fb802139d4645eed30f9865017a742607c185/resources/nodes/HingeJointParameters.wrl#L15) which could be fine as long as the global ones are also at default. If they aren't however  it doesn't respect it and imposes 0.2 and 1e-5 anyway. In other words  currently the global values are imposed to the stops if and only if `jointParameters` isn't defined which isn't enough.    The proposed solution uses `-1` to represent that the global values must be enforced.

Title: Add URDF CLI converter
Body: Currently  in ROS we are struggling to get URDF of a PROTO file. This PR should add a CLI verb that allows conversion from Webots PROTO to URDF and other supported formats (like `wbo` and `wrl`). The command should look like this:  ```bash  webots convert -p extensionSlot="Box {}" ${WEBOTS_HOME}/projects/robots/adept/pioneer3/protos/Pioneer3dx.proto exported.urdf  ```    That way we will be able to use Webots PROTOs just like `xacro`.    **Documentation**  https://cyberbotics.com/doc/guide/starting-webots?version=feature-cli-converter    **Tasks**    - [x] Add basic exporter    - [x] Fix URDF export    - [x] Pass arguments    - [x] Add field parsers    - [x] Document    - [x] Changelog    **Performance**  We anticipated low performance as Webots has to load a lot of shared libraries.     The following log shows a converting time of the Pioneer 3-DX PROTO to VRML (starting Webots  parsing  exporting  writing to the file):  ```  real    0m0.456s  user    0m0.308s  sys     0m0.137s  ```  I believe that the result (just under 0.5s) is very good  probably more efficient than a standalone script written in Python.     **Important notes**    This is the minimal code for creating a PROTO instance:  ```c++  // First  we populate the global variables (paths) in the `WbProtoList`  // `WbProtoList` will be later used to find sub-PROTOs  new WbProtoList(QFileInfo(inputFile).absoluteDir().path());    // Create a PROTO model  // When the `InstantiateMode` is turned off then the parser creates only `WbNode`  not derived classes (e.g. WbGroup)  // The `InstantiateMode` has to be turned off here as `WbProtoList::readModel` will not work otherwise  // The `worldPath` parameter is irrelevant  it is passed all over the parser just to be handed over to the Lua context  WbNode::setInstantiateMode(false);  WbProtoModel *model = WbProtoList::current()->readModel(inputFile  "");    // We need create an array of `WbField` objects for the PROTO instance  // We can use default values from the model or override them  QVector<WbField *> fields;  for (WbFieldModel *model : model->fieldModels())    fields.append(new WbField(model));    // For exporting the URDF we need `WbNode` derived objects so we have to turn on the `InstantiateMode`   WbNode::setInstantiateMode(true);  WbNode *node = WbNode::regenerateProtoInstanceFromParameters(model  fields  false  "");  ```

Title: Rework static proto tag logic
Body: **Description**  The current `static` tag can be somewhat misleading as typically it isn't mandatory (but suggested as an optimization) but not putting it can however lead to results such as in #2852 where the lack of the tag makes it misbehave with respect to restarts.    As suggested  the `static` behavior should be made the default case and instead a `nonDeterministic` tag is added for situations where multiple instances of a PROTO are meant to generate different results even when they have the same parameters (typically when randomness is involved).    The conversion steps undertaken are:  1. Filtering of the PROTO files that contain any of the keywords: time  seed  random  ```  projects/samples/robotbenchmark/pit_escape/protos/Pit.proto  projects/samples/rendering/protos/PingPongBallScaled.proto  projects/robots/saeon/protos/Altino.proto  projects/robots/kinematics/tinkerbots/protos/TinkerbotsAxle.proto  projects/objects/factory/conveyors/protos/ConveyorPlatform.proto  projects/objects/factory/conveyors/protos/ConveyorBelt.proto  projects/objects/trees/protos/SimpleTree.proto           <-- context.id based  projects/objects/trees/protos/Forest.proto               <-- time-based  projects/objects/floors/protos/UnevenTerrain.proto       <-- time-based  projects/objects/buildings/protos/StripBuilding.proto    <-- time-based  projects/samples/robotbenchmark/inverted_pendulum/protos/InvertedPendulumBenchmark.proto  projects/objects/factory/pallet/protos/WoodenPalletStack.proto <-- context.id based  projects/objects/buildings/protos/RandomBuilding.proto   <-- context.id based Title: Rework of hinge2withbacklash sequence
Body: **Description**  Issue described in #2898 is a consequence of using a Hinge2Joint for the neck as both the bracket and the head are now in the `endPoint` of the joint they will both move around the anchor. So for the head to behave as it should (which is what matters given the sensors)  the bracket will not look right.    To keep the performance gains of the hinge2joint will retaining a visual behavior that is correct for the neck piece  it required reworking the `Hinge2JointWithBacklash` proto by altering the sequence of the joints. From Hinge2Joint -> HingeJoint -> HingeJoint to HingeJoint -> Hinge2Joint -> HingeJoint and using the `startPoint` field for the neck bracket.      Neck behavior after the change:    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/112602860-806c3f80-8e14-11eb-9a5c-5421731638f4.mp4    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/112602863-819d6c80-8e14-11eb-8458-3d7bbacddfe4.mp4

Title: Remove conditional around startpoint for HingeJointWithBacklash
Body: **Description**  The conditional here  as is  doesn't actually work as `startPoint` is actually a MF and can't be checked against `nil`. Irrespective of that  having the conditional to begin with is undesirable as if this block doesn't exist when loading a world  users can't add anything to the `startPoint` since no compatible nodes show up in the interface.

Title: Updating Darwin opHinge2 proto with virtual RoboCup procedure
Body: The main parameters of the joints and motors are now accessible using local  variables (as it was done for backlash).    This change has the following impacts for all joints:    - maxTorque is slightly decrease (2.5 -> 2.3)  - maxVelocity is strongly decreased (12.26 -> 5.24)  - dampingConstant is strongly increased (0.002 -> 0.27)  - staticFriction is strongly increased (0.025 -> 0.80)  - resolution of the sensor is now limited    Impact of the behavior has been tested in the following way: on a RoboCup field   the robot can still walk and stand-up from both side.    **Additional context**    Note that the procedure might still evolve  but the parameters are now much closer to what should be announced by the teams for this kind of motors.

Title: Add wb_supervisor_node_get_pose function
Body: Often  users ask for an easy way to get a relative translation and rotation between two objects. This function resolves that issue.    Furthermore  this function is more efficient than manually calculating transformation between two objects as everything is done in a single request (compared to 4 requests otherwise  2 x (orientation + position)).    **Documentation**  https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/supervisor?version=feature-relative-pose    **Tasks**  - [x] Add Supervisor C API  - Add support for other languages:    - [x] C++    - [x] Python    - [x] Java    - [x] Matlab    - [x] ROS  - [x] Documentation  - [x] Tests  - [x] Check scale  - [x] ROS tests  - [x] Controller.def + WbLanguage.cpp  - [x] Changelog    **Test**  ```python  from controller import Supervisor      def check(a  b):      assert abs(a - b) < 0.005  f'{a} != {b}'      robot = Supervisor()  while robot.step(int(robot.getBasicTimeStep())) != -1:      pose = robot.getSelf().getPose(robot.getRoot())      # pose = robot.getSelf().getPose()      orientation = robot.getSelf().getOrientation()      position = robot.getSelf().getPosition()            for i  j in enumerate([0  1  2  4  5  6  8  9  10]):          check(pose[j]  orientation[i])            check(pose[3]  position[0])      check(pose[7]  position[1])      check(pose[11]  position[2])  ```

Title: Hotfix lib controller update after reset
Body: Fix #2992: when the simulation is reset  all the pending answers to the controllers were also reset including the fields and nodes updates due to the nodes deleted during the reset.  But if the controller is not restarted  we should not reset the pending answers because the controller is still running and it is still waiting for these messages.    The new message to update the fields count in the libController has been added in R2021b.  Some workarounds exists to prevent Webots to crash that can be applied on R2021a rev1.

Title: Feature robocup controllers
Body: I will continue the development of the referee on this branch  which is more convenient to run the tests. Once everything works  we could merge it to the Webots repository.    ### List of the bugs appearing through automated testing  - [x] Time management has to be updated    - Currently not guaranteeing that each step is not faster than...    - Real time waited is longer if the simulator can't match the real_time_factor in average  - [ ] Scoring goals from the different kind of Game Interruptions    - See all 'scoring' scenarios in 'game_interruptions'  - [x] Scoring goals from KickOff    - See 'game_phases/kick_off/'  scenarios 2 and 4  - [x] Penalty when opponent enters center circle while ball is not in play    - See 'game_phases/kick_off/'  scenarios 1 and 2  - [x] Dropped ball not implemented    - See 'game_phases/dropped_ball'  - [x] Illegally positioned robots are not penalized in SET after a goal    - See 'game_phases/repositioning'  - [ ] Problem on the INITIAL duration of the second half-time    - After 17 real-time seconds state has not changed (real_time factor 0.1)  see above    - Tested separately  even 30 minutes of simulated time after (5 minutes real-time)  state still hasn't changed (with default world)    - This problem impacts 'game_phases/second_half'  'results/win' and  'results/draw'  - [x] Robots staying out of the turf for more than 20 seconds are not penalized    - See 'misc_fouls/leaving_field'  - [ ] Inactive goalies are not penalized    - See 'misc_fouls/inactive_goalie'  - [x] Robot falling partially on the opponent side in the SET phase is not penalized    - See 'positioning/ready' (and issue 26)  - [ ] Robots might receive a penalty for being outside of the field during SET after the Autoref sent a PLAYING message to the GameController which leads to robots being sometime penalized at the start of PLAYING.    - This one is a little bit tricky because it might involve the order in which actions are applied in the GameController side.    - See 'positioning/initial' (it has been updated for clarifying the bug)    ### List of the bugs appearing through manual testing  - [ ] Transition to PLAYING from SET is sometimes failing after a goal or after 1st half  - [ ] For penalty shootouts:    - Ball is placed on the center circle  not on the penalty mark    - The transition between the states is not always working automatically    - End of the game is not detected

Title: Fix initial labels in streaming viewer mode
Body: **Description**  The labels are now send along the updates of positions/rotations/...    The labels that are set before the connection with the streaming viewer are sent with the first update.    However  it happens that this first update is droped by the streaming viewer because the scene is not fully loaded.    As labels are HTML elements  it is not a problem if some nodes or textures are not loaded  we can already draw them.    **Fix**  Instead of fully dropping an update if the scene is still loading  we drop everything but the labels.    Additionally  we restore the correct link in the animation template (the file will be changed on the server when merging)

Body: Fixes the mentioned in the https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/pull/3032#pullrequestreview-657983394 comment. Probably the Camera was affected as well.    **Steps to reproduce**  Compared to the steps explained in the comment we should be more aggressive to reproduce the crash almost every time:    - open `range_finder.wbt`    - start the simulation    - change the RangeFinder image width and height to 1000    - change the RangeFinder.spherical value to TRUE    **Additional context**  The `WbRenderingDevice` doesn't support changing the camera resolution at runtime. However  changing the `spherical` parameter fires an event that setups the `WbRenderingDevice` again. Setting up the `WbRenderingDevice` with the new resolution during the runtime crashes the simulation.    I am not sure whether the bug is present in the master branch.

Title: Improve camera performance
Body: **Description**  This PR improves performances of the `wb_camera_get_image` function by 1000x (from ~2000us to ~2us). At the moment  it is a raw implementation  I still have to check for side effects.    Interestingly  in our ROS 2 performance benchmark  there are no performance improvements. It is probably because the bottleneck is the mutex lock rather than unnecessary processing.

Title: Recursively search for finalized PROTO node
Body: Fix #3034:  fix the search for PROTO parameter node instance considering only one nested layer.  So accessing parameters of multiple nested PROTO nodes were not correctly handled causing assertion failures and crashes due to request of physical properties to non-finalized intermediate nodes.    This will be the simpler solution for users because they do not need to know the internal sub PROTO node definitions.  However  it is faster to already get the parameter node instance (or the closest node as possible) from the robot controller.

Title: Fix crash solidReference
Body: **Description**  Webots crashed when we were inserting a solidReference and the top node of this solidReference was a transform or a group.  For example: Transform->Solid->HingeJoint->SolidReference.    With the introduction in developp of the possibility to introduce robots in transform  Webots would crash if we inserted the Shrimp robot in a transform.    CAUSE: to get the top solid  Webots was retrieving the top node and casting it to solid. But in the case of a group or transform as the top node  it would fail.    FIX: instead of retrieving the top node  we retrieve the uppest solid.    **Related Issues**  This pull-request fixes issue #3037

Title: Fix triangle count
Body: **Description**  The triangle count for `Mesh`/`IndexedFaceSet` shows `0` when there is too many triangles.     ![noshadow](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/38250944/119150747-055b8a00-ba4f-11eb-9449-1add1d1d153b.png)    This is because the count function relies on the size of the `triangles` vector from the `wren`. However  the renderer currently does not  display shadows  for meshes with more than (2^16-1)/3 triangles  to avoid an overflow of the index. Thus the `triangles` vector is empty.    This PR instead directly use the `indexCount` (divided by 3) to get the number of triangles. Also  it displays `(no shadow)` next to the number of triangles if it is beyond the limit for which Webots casts shadows.    ![corrected](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/38250944/119151726-f5907580-ba4f-11eb-8dd6-8dcff4253aea.png)    **Linked PR**  [Enhancement display triangles geometry node](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/pull/1456)

Title: Remove hidden parameter field connection
Body: **Description**  The proposed fix removes the connection for hidden fields  which are source of overhead in the `postPhysics` step  specifically `linearVelocity` and `angularVelocity` of solids. This solution is more proper than the one considered in #2927.  The larger issue of the overhead with nested PROTO will be addressed in that PR.      As can be seen  the saving of a world mid-execution still works as intended.  ```  #VRML_SIM R2021b utf8  WorldInfo {    coordinateSystem "NUE"  }  Viewpoint {    position 0 0 1.2232405575066063  }  TexturedBackground {  }  TexturedBackgroundLight {  }  MainProtoSimple {    hidden linearVelocity_1 0 -3.9793883743761297e-10 0    hidden angularVelocity_1 0 0.2 0    condition TRUE    pos 0.7551999999333323    rot 0 1 0 0.7551974221411469  }  ```    As for the performance impact  it was tested on the `kid.wbt` world and these are the results.  Without the fix:  ```  <mode> <stepsCount> <prePhysics(ms)> <physics(ms)> <postPhysics(ms)> <mainRendering(ms)> <virtualRealityHeadsetRendering(ms)> <gpuMemoryTransfer(ms)> <trianglesCount> <mainFPS> <device:Camera(ms)> <controller:soccer(ms)>  AVG            4000            0.263        18.136             3.448              25.415                                0.000                   0.089              nan     0.000               0.213                   5.839   TOT            4000         1050.070     72542.964         13792.519             101.658                                0.000                   0.709            0.000     0.000            3420.957               23423.677     ```  With the fix:  ```  <mode> <stepsCount> <prePhysics(ms)> <physics(ms)> <postPhysics(ms)> <mainRendering(ms)> <virtualRealityHeadsetRendering(ms)> <gpuMemoryTransfer(ms)> <trianglesCount> <mainFPS> <device:Camera(ms)> <controller:soccer(ms)>  AVG            4000            0.259        18.233             3.021              26.446                                0.000                   0.085              nan     0.000               0.210                   5.828   TOT            4000         1035.593     72932.316         12083.677             105.785                                0.000                   0.681            0.000     0.000            3368.223               23379.065     ```    Which roughly corresponds to a change in the real-time factor from 0.26x to 0.29x (on a not so strong computer).

Title: Fix Camera lens distortion
Body: Fix #2295 and #2934:  Camera lens distortion uses the Brown's distortion model  but there were bugs in the implementation and the center was not used for the radial and tagential components.  Additional  to apply lens distortion it is needed to apply an inverted Brown's distortion model.    Now  the distortion is correctly applied both in X and Y directions  as well as symmetrically on the right/left of the image. Here is the result using `Lens { center = [0.5  0.5]  radialCoefficients = [-0.5  0]  tangetialCoefficients = [0  0]}`:    ![lens_distortion](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5910449/114714022-fdaf1400-9d31-11eb-89a6-52df093f8a67.png)

Title: Fix updating Lidar type during simulation run
Body: Many internal structures (WREN camera  image arrays  etc.) depends on the `Lidar.type` value but the size of these structure was not updated when then `Lidar.type` was changed causing some issues in particular when switching from "rotating" to "fixed" (height and width of the lidar is bigger for the "fixed" type).  Here are some of the issues:  - crash #2982 when executing the `memset` instruction in the `WbLidar::reset` method  - wrong graphical point cloud representation    There are already a number of fields for Camera (width  height) and Lidar (fieldOfView  verticalFieldOfView  horizontalResolution  numberOfLayers) nodes whose modification is only applied after saving and reloading the world.  So the best and more consistent fix is to require saving and reloading the world also to change the Lidar type.

Title: Fix incorrect device limit constraints in Hinge2Joint and BallJoint
Body: **Related Issues**  This pull-request fixes issue #2823.    **Description**  As mentioned in issue #2823  device position limits ( `maxPosition` and `minPosition` on `device2`) appear to be checked against `position` field of `jointParameters` instead of `jointParameters2`.    According to the ODE documentation  this is said about hinge2joint    > Axis 1 can have joint limits and a motor  axis 2 can only have a motor.     To my understanding  joint limits refers to `minStop` and `maxStop` whereas in this particular case we're talking about _motor limits_  which I believe axis2 can have independently to axis1 and leads me to believe that issue #2823 is indeed a bug.    The bug stems from 2 factors:  - In [updateMinAndMaxPosition](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/c0ce8250876997125c4decbeed48bf0f98e39e0b/src/webots/nodes/WbMotor.cpp#L175) no distinction between the axis is made and `jointParameters` is always picked.  - In [WbJointDevice](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/c0ce8250876997125c4decbeed48bf0f98e39e0b/src/webots/nodes/WbJointDevice.cpp#L51-L61) the attribution of `mPositionIndex` occurs only in the `postFinalize` step whereas [updateMinAndMaxPosition](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/c0ce8250876997125c4decbeed48bf0f98e39e0b/src/webots/nodes/WbMotor.cpp#L99) is called in the `preFinalize` one meaning that it would always default to the first axis anyway.    Technically after fixing the first bug it would've sufficed to call `updateMinAndMaxPosition` in `postFinalize` instead of `preFinalize` to achieve the same result  but the proposed solution seems more consistent with the rest of the code (to me at least).

Title: Update the list of exported images when streaming to x3d
Body: **Description**  Currently the list of textures that webots can serve to the streaming-viewer is defined only when the world is exported as x3d.    The problem is that if we add appearances with new textures to the simulation while it is streaming  the new textures will not be added to the list and therefore not served to the streaming-viewer.    I solved this issue by adding the new textures to the existing list when the server exports new nodes to the streaming-viewer.

Title: update textures while streaming
Body: **Description**  Currently the list of textures that webots can serve to the streaming-viewer is defined only when the world is exported as x3d.    The problem is that if we add appearances with new textures to the simulation while it is streaming  the new textures will not be added to the list and therefore not served to the streaming-viewer.    I solved this issue by adding the new textures to the existing list when the server exports new nodes to the streaming-viewer.

Title: delete step message
Body: **Description**  Webots is sending text messages along update messages (containing time  new position ...). These text messages can be: "pause"  "real-time"  "fast" and "step". The three first are used to change the appearance of the buttons in the toolbar of the streaming-viewer. But the "step" message is not used. In fact it is not even handle in the streaming-viewer  resulting in ```WebSocket error: Unknown message received "step"```.    As we don't use it  I removed it from webots.

Title: regenerate x3d world at loading
Body: **Description**  Sometimes  the x3d world in not regenerated by webots when reloading the world even so the world has changed.    Minimal example:  -launch webots with ```--stream```  -create a simple cube  -save the world  -open and connect the streaming-viewer  you should see the cube  -disconnect the streaming-viewer.  -delete the cube  -save and reload the simulation.  -connect the streaming-viewer  you should still see the cube in the streaming-viewer even so it is no more in webots.    To solve this  I removed the conditions such that now the x3dworld is regenerated every time we reload the world.

Title: use closest contact for ray collision
Body: **Related Issues**  This pull-request addresses issue #2605    **Description**  The root of the problem appears to be that IndexedFaceSets are different to classic Solids with regards to ray collision. With solids like boxes and spheres there appears to be always only one point of contact (n = 1 [here](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/3766a52ca250cc6ba41a777182a4aeb61d2d3642/src/webots/engine/WbSimulationCluster.cpp#L582-L585)) which might explain why the collision callback:    > ds->rayCollisionCallback(odeGeomData2->geometry()  o1  &contact[0].geom);    is always called with `contact[0]`. With IndexedFaceSets however there can be more  I'm not sure if more than 2 but at least 2 for a box-like shape built using IndexedFaceSets  as shown in this video.     https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/103298156-089b9e00-49fa-11eb-8510-e8fd0fe9934a.mp4    As can be seen the problem then arises from the fact that it isn't guaranteed that contact[0] is the closest  in fact it appears to never be. Since `dCollide()` returned the contact point on the opposite face as first element  the angle computed [here](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/3766a52ca250cc6ba41a777182a4aeb61d2d3642/src/webots/nodes/WbDistanceSensor.cpp#L545-L548) when the contact is handled evaluates in this case to 180¬∞ ( `angle = direction.angle(-normal)` ) and the ray is therefore ignored because outside the 45¬∞ cone which explains why it always returns max value as mentioned in issue #2605.    The suggested fix then is to use the closest contact among the `n` returned by `dCollide()`;    Here's the same video after the fix:    https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/103298149-05081700-49fa-11eb-8bbf-4225e258a602.mp4    **Test world used**  [distance_sensor_bug.zip](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/files/5751497/distance_sensor_bug.zip)      **Related (possible) pitfalls**  It doesn't appear to be at the origin of the problem here  but the `TexturedBox.proto` (technically `TexturedParallelepiped.proto`) primitive uses a IndexedFaceSet to define the parallelepiped  and the faces are defined as squares (4 vertices) whereas according to the IndexedFaceSet documentation     > When used for collision detection (boundingObject)  each face of the IndexedFaceSet must contain exactly three vertices  hence defining a triangle mesh (or trimesh).    Considering more often than not TexturedBoxes will use their own shape as boundingObject  it might be better to re-define them as such. It doesn't appear to create any issue as is  despite being defined as 4-vertices faces there appears to be a mechanism somewhere that splits them into triangles the correct way (or just out of luck) so the issue mentioned here might return if the automatic splitting is altered at some point and the normals of some of the triangles aren't in the correct direction (rays being ignored again because the angle is outside the 45¬∞ cone). Unless of course the splitting isn't random at all  in which case it will be fine.

Title: Enhancement of vehicle rear lights for mercedes lincoln citroen bmw and rangerover
Body: **Description**    - the existing mesh  where possible  was split/adjusted to make use of the [VehicleLights](https://www.cyberbotics.com/doc/automobile/car#vehiclelights) primitive so that the rear car lights react accordingly to the different Driver calls. No new meshes were added  just reworked the existing ones.  - the documentation for VehicleLights ([car.md](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/master/docs/automobile/car.md)) was updated according to the values present in the [proto](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/master/projects/vehicles/protos/abstract/VehicleLights.proto) (default color values were wrong)     PS: I've attempted to keep the general location of the lights correct with their real counterpart  but sometimes was tricky not knowing the year of the cars    **Test world**  [rear_indicators.zip](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/files/5760636/rear_indicators.zip)      **Related Issues**  This pull-request solves issue #2600    **When `wbu_driver_set_cruising_speed(-10)`**  ![reverse](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/103462616-c38fa880-4d26-11eb-9426-bf61fc0f8752.png)  notes: no change    **When calling `wbu_driver_set_antifog_lights`**  ![antifog](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/103462666-149f9c80-4d27-11eb-88d2-9f0dc4434ce8.png)  notes: the citroen c-zero rear fog light is white because this car is the only one with front fog lights working  and distinction between front and rear colors can't be made at the moment    **When calling `wbu_driver_set_dipped_beams`**  ![dipped_beam](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/103462753-bcb56580-4d27-11eb-804b-cad885849228.png)  notes: most light meshes were in this category (basically everything lights up)  so they've been separated. The mercedes ones were just wrong. The citroen one was split to serve multiple purposes (like in reality)    **When calling `wbu_driver_set_brake_intensity(1.0)`**  ![braking](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/103462890-c12e4e00-4d28-11eb-8d81-3c9036d4bbe8.png)  notes: despite having emissivity like blinkers  it doesn't currently show it much (compare with hazard lights below)  not sure why.    **When calling `wbu_driver_set_hazard_flashers` (or the left/right indicators)**  ![indicators](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/103463066-eb344000-4d29-11eb-9d90-70cfc7be149e.png)  notes: for the BMW (4th car) I took the mesh from the body of the car  which as far as I can tell it's the way it looks in older BMW x5 cars (which from the shape it appears to be)  if it's a more recent model  then it's technically the wrong spot  assuming it matters.

Title: Expose new API for accessing RangeFinder s raw float buffer in Python
Body: **Description**    This PR introduces a new `data_type` keyword parameter on the `getRangeImage` method. The default value  `list`  preserves its existing behavior. The new alternative  `buffer`  returns a `bytes` object with a copy of the machine-dependent `float` buffer.    The behavior of `getRangeImageArray` is unchanged. I opted to add the new functionality to `getRangeImage` rather than `getRangeImageArray` because a byte buffer more closely resembles a 1D list than 2D. ü§∑     **Related Issues**    Fixes issue #2661. There's a full description in that issue.    API is modelled after #2321.    **Tasks**    I don't know what tasks I'm supposed to put here  but... I added the option and updated the documentation.    I have _not_ introduced a changelog entry.    **Documentation**    This MR is sourced from my fork for politeness; I believe I could push the branch to the upstream repo and change the source if that's what is preferred.    **Additional context**    <details>  <summary>Not-very-scientific test controller</summary>    ```python  from controller import Robot    import time  import numpy as np  import cv2    robot = Robot()    timestep = int(robot.getBasicTimeStep())    rf = robot.getDevice("range-finder")  rf.enable(int(robot.getBasicTimeStep()))    i = 0  while robot.step(timestep) != -1:      if i % 2 == 0:          start = time.time()          image = rf.getRangeImage(data_type="list")          image_np = np.array(image).reshape(rf.getHeight()  rf.getWidth())          end = time.time()          #cv2.imwrite("list.png"  np.array(image_np * 100  dtype=np.uint8))          print(f"List time: {(end-start)*1000:.2f} ms")      else:          start = time.time()          image = rf.getRangeImage(data_type="buffer")          image_np = np.frombuffer(image  dtype=np.float32).reshape(rf.getHeight()  rf.getWidth())          end = time.time()          #cv2.imwrite("buffer.png"  np.array(image_np * 100  dtype=np.uint8))          print(f"Buffer time: {(end-start)*1000:.2f} ms")      i += 1    ```  </details>    On my machine  with a 640x480 image (formatted as `median` / `mean`):    -|list|buffer  ---|---|---  function call only | 8ms / 8.7ms | 5ms / 5.5ms  function call plus numpy array | 22ms / 24.5ms | 7ms / 7.6ms    I'm not 100% satisfied with this performance (7ms is still rather high for what should  ideally  do effectively zero work) but I figure it's worth opening the PR for discussion.

Title: proto2mesh
Body: **Description**  This script aims at converting all the PROTO files distributed in Webots to replace the IndexedFaceSet nodes with Mesh nodes referring to OBJ files.    The benefits are manifold:  - The loading time of the PROTO files should be greatly improved.  - The readability of the PROTO file will be improved (way smaller files).  - The OBJ files could be edited separately (in Blender or other 3D editor) without having to re-export to VRML97 and copy/paste the IndexedFaceSet in the PROTO file.  - The same OBJ files could be used by different PROTO files.    **Preliminary results:** loading 10 UR3e robots using OBJ files take 12 seconds on my computer while it takes 27 seconds to load 10 original UR3e robots using IndexedFaceSet. I suppose the benefit comes from the fact that the creaseAngle doesn't need to be computed for OBJ files (which is a pretty intensive computation).    This PR includes an example of converted PROTO file: the RubberDuck.proto.  It was also successfully tested against the UR3e robot PROTO file.  Once accepted we should open new PRs to convert more complex PROTO files  including robots.
