Title: fix reproductibility issue when resetting
Body: This is gonna be a little long winded but it's kinda necessary.    **Related issue**  This fix addresses issue #2658    **Test world**  Same as #2658  just printing to console instead of to file for simplicity. Results are the same in this case.    **Description**  To summarize  the situation is :  - ROBOT_A (is a supervisor)    - has a controller `position_tracker`    - this controller spawns ROBOT_B and tracks it  - ROBOT_B (is a supervisor)    - has a controller  `dummy_controller`    - this controller applies a force to itself    After looking into it the lack of reproducibility boils down to these 2 situations that should be equal but aren't.     **Situation (1)**  1. load scenario  2. step  step  step  step (call this output RESULTS_1)  3. reset from GUI  4. step  step  step  step (call this output RESULTS_2)  5. reset from GUI  6. step  step  step  step (call this output RESULTS_3)    **conclusion:** no issues  RESULTS_1 = RESULTS_2 = RESULTS_3    **Situation (2)**    1. load scenario  2. run simulation (call this output RESULTS_1)  3. reset from GUI  4. (simulations runs again by itself) (call this output RESULTS_2)  5. reset from GUI  6. (simulations runs again by itself) (call this output RESULTS_3)    **conclusion:** RESULTS_2 = RESULTS_3 but RESULTS_1 is not equal to either    Looking closer at the differences  it's oddly small and doesn't really diverge  ```  RESULT_1  step   : x                  y                   z  0.0320 : 0.0000000000000000 -0.0001024000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.0640 : 0.0000474074074074 -0.0003072000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.0960 : 0.0001422222222222 -0.0006144000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.1280 : 0.0002844444444444 -0.0010240000000000 0.0000000000000000  RESULT_2  0.0320 : 0.0000000000000000 -0.0001024000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.0640 : 0.0000000000000000 -0.0003072000000000 0.0000000000000000 <-- shenanigans (spoiler: caused by gravity)  0.0960 : 0.0000474074074074 -0.0006144000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.1280 : 0.0001422222222222 -0.0010240000000000 0.0000000000000000  ```  When checking the data  the **x** of RESULT_2 is just like RESULT_1 but shifted by one timestep and the **y** is unchanged.  This remains true for much longer captures  and any consecutive reset will look exactly like RESULT_2 so it is   reproducible from a physics standpoint but not from a "logic" one  basically the first run and the successive ones don't do the same "thing".    This is situation (1) code-wise  through some console prints inside function `WbControlledWorld::step` :  ```  world is loaded  << USER INPUT: STEP <<<  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=1]) <-- sequence of step() calls that don't reach    WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])     the end  of the function  controllers are   WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])     spawned etc  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])   WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0]) <-- notice that we're paused  as we're   WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])     doing it step by step  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])  -- controllers at the END of the function WbControlledWorld::step  - mNewControllers:  - mWaitingControllers:  - mControllers:                                                  <-- when we finally reach the end of the       position_tracker: isRunning? YES                                 function  both controllers are in       dummy_controller: isRunning? YES                                 mControllers and both are running  CALLING WbSimulationWorld::step()                                <-- doing the simulation step  done  << USER INPUT: STEP <<<  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=1])  -- controllers at the END of the function WbControlledWorld::step  - mNewControllers:  - mWaitingControllers:  - mControllers:      position_tracker: isRunning? YES      dummy_controller: isRunning? YES  CALLING WbSimulationWorld::step()                                <-- same  all is fine  done  << USER INPUT: RESET FROM GUI <<<                                <-- manual reset  << USER INPUT: STEP <<<  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=1])   WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])    WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])    WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=1][isStep=0])  -- controllers at the END of the function WbControlledWorld::step  - mNewControllers:  - mWaitingControllers:  - mControllers:      position_tracker: isRunning? YES      dummy_controller: isRunning? YES  CALLING WbSimulationWorld::step()                                 <-- again by the time we reach the end     done                                                                  the controllers are up and running  << USER INPUT: STEP <<<  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=1])  -- controllers at the END of the function WbControlledWorld::step  - mNewControllers:  - mWaitingControllers:  - mControllers:      position_tracker: isRunning? YES      dummy_controller: isRunning? YES  CALLING WbSimulationWorld::step()  done    ```    and indeed the console output is  ```  INFO: position_tracker: Starting controller: python3 -u position_tracker.py  INFO: dummy_controller: Starting controller: python3 -u dummy_controller.py  0.0320 : 0.0000000000000000 -0.0001024000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.0640 : 0.0000474074074074 -0.0003072000000000 0.0000000000000000  INFO: position_tracker: Starting controller: python3 -u position_tracker.py  INFO: dummy_controller: Starting controller: python3 -u dummy_controller.py  0.0320 : 0.0000000000000000 -0.0001024000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.0640 : 0.0000474074074074 -0.0003072000000000 0.0000000000000000  ```  showing nothing anomalous.  Doing the same thing for situation (2) yields (the world was reloaded before doing this test):    ```  world is loaded  << USER INPUT: REALTIME <<<  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0]) <-- sequence of step() calls that don't reach   WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])     the end of the function  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0]) <-- notice that now we're not paused anymore  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  -- controllers at the END of the function WbControlledWorld::step  - mNewControllers:  - mWaitingControllers:  - mControllers:      position_tracker: isRunning? YES                             <-- the world was reloaded  so the starting       dummy_controller: isRunning? YES                                 procedure is the same as the previous     CALLING WbSimulationWorld::step()                                    case  hence  all is good so far   done    [ ... more steps like this ... ]                                 <-- everything fine  RESULT_1 won't change    << USER INPUT: RESET FROM GUI <<<                                <-- manual reset  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])   WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  -- controllers at the END of the function WbControlledWorld::step  - mNewControllers:      dummy_controller: isRunning? NO                              <-- effect of the reset  - mWaitingControllers:  - mControllers:      position_tracker: isRunning? YES  CALLING WbSimulationWorld::step()                                <-- here's the culprit  a simulation step is  done                                                                 taken despite one of the controllers not  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])     yet active  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  WbControlledWorld::step (SimulationState [isPaused=0][isStep=0])  -- controllers at the END of the function WbControlledWorld::step  - mNewControllers:  - mWaitingControllers:  - mControllers:      position_tracker: isRunning? YES                             <-- the other timesteps are fine  but since       dummy_controller: isRunning? YES                                 we've made a simulation step we shouldn't    CALLING WbSimulationWorld::step()                                    it won't produce the same result  done    [ ... more steps like this ... ]                                 <-- running  ```    and the console output is  ```  INFO: position_tracker: Starting controller: python3 -u position_tracker.py  INFO: dummy_controller: Starting controller: python3 -u dummy_controller.py  0.0320 : 0.0000000000000000 -0.0001024000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.0640 : 0.0000474074074074 -0.0003072000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.0960 : 0.0001422222222222 -0.0006144000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.1280 : 0.0002844444444444 -0.0010240000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.1600 : 0.0004740740740741 -0.0015360000000000 0.0000000000000000  INFO: position_tracker: Starting controller: python3 -u position_tracker.py  INFO: dummy_controller: Starting controller: python3 -u dummy_controller.py  0.0320 : 0.0000000000000000 -0.0001024000000000 0.0000000000000000  0.0640 : 0.0000000000000000 -0.0003072000000000 0.0000000000000000 <-- parasitic step  gravity affects box  0.0960 : 0.0000474074074074 -0.0006144000000000 0.0000000000000000 <-- from this point dummy_controller is      0.1280 : 0.0001422222222222 -0.0010240000000000 0.0000000000000000     up and running and it applies a   0.1600 : 0.0002844444444444 -0.0015360000000000 0.0000000000000000     force to itself  ```    The culprit is therefore a different resetting behavior for the two cases  and the reason is that either [L429-L433](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/592090f4e1967575e9f0bd5e984f9c43caa6ec1b/src/webots/control/WbControlledWorld.cpp#L429-L433) or [L445-L450](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/592090f4e1967575e9f0bd5e984f9c43caa6ec1b/src/webots/control/WbControlledWorld.cpp#L445-L450) (in this specific case it's this latter that triggers) the `dummy_controller` is added in one case to the mNewControllers list and in the other to the mWaitingControllers. According to the headers:  ```  QList<WbController *> mWaitingControllers;  // controllers inserted in previous step and waiting to be started in current step  QList<WbController *> mNewControllers;      // controllers inserted in current step mode and waiting next step to start  ```  So what happens is that in situation (1)  after the reset the `dummy_controller` is added and activated in the same step call hence by the time we reach the end of the function it's ready to go. In situation (2)   `dummy_controller`  is moved from mNewControllers to mWaitingController only AFTER a `WbSimulationWorld::step()` is executed ([change occurs here](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/592090f4e1967575e9f0bd5e984f9c43caa6ec1b/src/webots/control/WbControlledWorld.cpp#L361)).  Which explains the results obtained  as in this additional simulation step  nothing but gravity is affecting the box which results in the **y** dip and only in the successive step the controller kicks in  but that's enough for the data to mismatch.    **Proposed fix:**  execute the line `WbSimulationWorld::step()` only if `mNewControllers` is empty.    It gets the job done in this specific case and test_suite is all green  but I don't know if it messes up with the controller logic more in general. The starting procedure it's quite convoluted (between waiting for external controllers  and some being spawned by startControllers and others by other means) so although this seems like an appropriate fix I don't know if it might be overkill to prevent it every time since the problem so far appears only to arise in the specific situation of a reset. Whatever the case  at least it should clarify the origin of the problem.

Title: removal of the forced reset for solids with ballJoint parents that causes incorrect reset
Body: **Description**  The reset function of WbSolid explicitly treats solids having a ballJoint parent differently from all other types of joint  suggesting that in this particular case the parent doesn't take care of it  hence it forces a manual reset of these types of Solid to their initial values.    In practice  that doesn't appear to be the case  as the reset propagates through the chain just fine:    > BallJoint::reset() ---> WbHinge2Joint::reset() ---> WbJoint::reset() ---> WbBasicJoint::reset() ---> endpoint reset (in this case  the _upper_surface_ solid)    It also explains why in issue #2539 resetting twice the steward_platform.wbt works:    - **first reset:** _upper_surface_ solid forced to its initial position  then when the rest of the chain updates it messes up (the pistons reset fine  only _upper_surface_ isn't where it should be).  - **second reset:** since the rest of chain is now in the correct position  the second forced reset of the _upper_surface_ solid puts it where it should be    **Fix**  By removing this forced manual update for the specific case of a Solid having a BallJoint parent  the simulation reverts to the initial position correctly.    PS: the manual reset itself shouldn't be removed. It takes care of resetting free-floating objects (in this case the flying boxes) and resetting the root of the robot  from which the rest propagates.    **Tests**  visual validation of the fix in the following worlds:  - all files in samples/demos    The addition of a world having a highly jointed robot to use as testbench for the reset mechanism might be warranted    **Related Issues**  This pull-request fixes issue #2539    **Screenshots**  Before reset:  ![messed_up](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/102839089-033dc280-4400-11eb-8d1d-c48b04c6e261.png)  After reset:  ![after_reset](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/102839086-020c9580-4400-11eb-8cbc-1e158c5a617a.png)        **Additional context**  Add any other context about the pull-request here.

Title: Fix mismatch between slugify function in documentation test

As a result wrong anchors that won't work in the documentation are passing the tests instead of the correct ones.  In particular there are issues with text in parenthesis.    Also `showdown-extensions.js` doesn't properly convert the `+` symbols in its slugify function but just the first occurrence.

Title: Improve controller linking
Body: We add the `rpath` to better support a dynamic library loading in Python. Otherwise  we have to configure `LD_LIBRARY_PATH` before the `python3 myscript.py` call.    Unfortunately  this works fine only for Linux. For macOS  it may be possible (https://longwei.github.io/rpath_origin/)  but Windows doesn't support `rpath` at all (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42497999/build-project-with-libraries-in-other-directories-windows-mingw).

Body: **Description**  Replace the three.js parts of the documentation viewer with wrenjs.    **Tasks**    - [x] Replace webots.min.js by wrenjs    - [x] Fix wrong location of .hdr background    - [x] Hardcode 'NUE' in worldinfo    - [x] Add mention of the pip library needed by `web_component_studio`     - [x] Script loader    - [x] Adress the problem when switching between robot    - [x] Modify JSon and .x3d of ENU robots (robotis op2  pioneer 3 AT and tinkerbots)    - [x] Convert billboard panel in non three.js code    - [x] Improve it    - [x] Interface billboard and scene    - [x] Fix position of loading gif    - [x] Add sphere in the scene according to the billboard    - [x] Modernize the code of viewer.js      - [x] Var to const/let      - [x] Get rid of JQuery    **Before merging**  Rename request_methods_module.js en  request_methods.js    Change the branch on doc.php    **Link to test**  https://cyberbotics.com/doc/guide/aibo-ers7?version=feature-docs-wrenjs    **Remarks**    - To not break the offline documentation on develop  I was forced to restore the old request_methods on the server. Title: Addition of coupled motors
Body: **Description**  This PR introduces the ability to control multiple motors  that share the same name  at the same time.    **Working principle**  - Webots side  each motor keeps track of all other motors that have the same name as itself (based on `cMotors`). They all need to have this list because in principle any of them could be directly called (if `get_device_by_index` is used  if `get_device` is used  it will usually always be the first one)  - Whenever an API call is made  for e.g.  `wb_motor_set_velocity`  the motor under question handles the message and also relays the same command to its siblings  if any. Each will adapt this command according to their own `multiplier`.  - No changes to the tag assignment/indexing logic to maintain compatibility    **Tasks**    - [x] Core functionality      - [x] velocity control      - [x] torque control      - [x] position control    - [x] Demo    - [x] Unit test    - [x] Documentation    - [x] Cleanup

Title: Fix asymmetric friction
Body: **Description**  The asymmetric friction force direction is wrongly computed for `Cylinder` and `Box`.    Currently  the `computeFrictionDirection(const WbVector3 &normal)` of both of them try first to express the normal to the contact point into the local coordinates system of the `Cylinder`/`Box`.  However to do so  it uses `matrix().extracted3x3Matrix()` as transformation matrix  which corresponds to Local-->Global.    `WbVector3 localNormal =  matrix().extracted3x3Matrix() * normal;`    The issue is corrected by using the inverse matrix  which is here simply the transpose:    `WbVector3 localNormal = normal * matrix().extracted3x3Matrix();`.    Besides  in SimulationCluster.cpp  the naming of     `localFdirS1 = wg2->matrix().extracted3x3Matrix() * wg2->computeFrictionDirection(contactNormal);`    has been changed to globalFdirS1 for clarification (it is expressed in the global coordinates system  not local)      **Tasks**    - [x] Correct localNormal     - [x] Changed localFdirSx to globalFdirSx

Title: Add JavaScript support for procedural PROTO
Body: **Description**  This PR adds JavaScript support for Procedural PROTO files. Here  only the test suite has been converted. The conversion of the remaining library is done in a different PR.    As it will become clear in the review  supporting two different scripting languages (and specifically two different tokens) leads to some awkward choices like having to set the tokens multiple times during the execution (assumptions about the Template tokens are made long before a procedural protos are generated). To completely refactor the structure didn't make much sense since ultimately Lua will be dropped in the future. This means that until then there will be some additional overhead because of this.    **Performance**  Performance-wise  some degradation compared to Lua has been identified in certain cases:  - PROTO files that have many expressions. A typical case is where the IndexedFaceSet is built in a procedural way  coordinate by coordinate. A notable example is the `Fence.proto` that involves 20'000-50'000 javascript expression evaluations just to define the shape.  - Worlds that rely on the `Forest.proto`. Since it isn't possible to natively manipulate files in the engine  the text files that define the forests have been moved inside the world file. Since some of them involve 50'000+ trees  the parsing of these worlds drops to unacceptable levels.    Both issues are addressed in the relevant PR #3156 as it's more pertinent.    **Docs**  Concerning the docs  the functions exported by the modules have been also documented. Since this did not exist for Lua and nothing similar exists for JavaScript in the current docs  the route I took was to do this like this:    I believe having these tabs makes it more intuitive rather than having one huge list  but I'm open to do it differently if you don't think it's a good idea    ![docs](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/121530672-f0469b00-c9fd-11eb-8202-ccded49cbd9c.png)    **Lua end of support**    When Lua support is dropped  the following must be done:  - in the test suite:     - remove all PROTO files ending in `*Lua.proto`     - remove all worlds ending in `*lua.wbt`  - in all PROTO files  remove the `# template language: javascript` from the header  - search if any PROTO files with template tokens `%{   }%` persist. If so  delete or convert them.  - in `WbProtoModel.cpp`     - in `WbProtoModel::WbProtoModel`: basically undo all changes made in this PR and replace the hard-coded tokens with the new ones     - in `WbProtoModel::generateRoot`: remove member variable mTemplateLanguage and anything else that uses it  - in `WbTokenizer.cpp`: undo all changes made by this PR  - in `WbProtoTemplateEngine.cpp`: remove the `convertStatementFromJavaScriptToLua` function.  - in `WbTemplateEngine.cpp`:      - remove references to lua (`generateLua`  `initializeLua` and global variables.)     - remove `copyModuleToTemporaryFile`

Title: Add force torque scale factor to Worldinfo
Body: **Description**  This PR adds two new fields to `WorldInfo`: `dragForceScale` and `dragTorqueScale`. They allow the user to set the order of magnitude of the force/torque applied to a `Solid` inside the Webots interface when doing (Alt+Click). Indeed  it is sometimes difficult to apply a force/torque in the desired range when dragging the mouse. The force is computed as follow:     *F* [N] = `dragForceScale` * `Solid.mass` * *d*<sup> 3</sup>  where *d* corresponds to the vector created by dragging the mouse (in meters)     instead of F [N] = _constant_ * *d*<sup> 3</sup> (nothing changes except we can set the value of the _constant_).    The torque is computed in the same idea:    *T* [Nm] = `dragTorqueScale` * `Solid.mass` * *d*<sup> 3</sup>     instead of T [Nm] = _constant_  * `Solid.mass` * *d*   (we have the cube of *d* here to be consistent with the computation of the force. Also  it enables to increase slowly when *d*<1 which is good as the object goes easily out of bounds when the applied torque is too high).    The default values of the added fields corresponds to the _constant_ values that are currently used (`dragForceScale` = 30 and `dragTorqueScale` = 5)

Title: Fix reconnecting extern controllers
Body: Replaces #3005.  Fixes: #3000 and #1903    > If the controller died  it can't call the cleanup function  and when I restart it  I get a error message from webots because he think that the controller is still running  so he can't find a spot for the new incoming connection.    > It simply remove the dead controller connection as usual  then recreate a new one.  The trick is to use the name of the robot to know which dead controller should be kill.  Otherwise  if no name is provided  the code execute as usual (scanning for free spot).    In case a single extern controller is defined  then the robot name is not needed and the currently connected controller is terminated and reconnected.

Title: Allows failed controller to reconnect to a robot
Body: If the controller died  it can't call the cleanup function  and when I restart it  I get a error message from webots because he think that the controller is still running  so he can't find a spot for the new incoming connection.    It simply remove the dead controller connection as usual  then recreate a new one. (a bit of code duplication from the line above  my bad... It might be possible to avoid that).  The trick is to use the name of the robot to know which dead controller should be kill. (which is fine for me). Otherwise  if no name is provided  the code execute as usual (scanning for free spot).    Maybe a more elegant solution is possible  by reassigning a socket id  for instance  but I'm first trying to get it working. I've noticed the robot_id  which maybe could be used for that  but I've not investigated in that direction.  It's have not been tested in every way possible  but I'm not seeing major issues coming.  The main thing to check would be leak of memory  unclosed socket and so on  because I'm not sure how is it performed.    I'm open to any advice   it's my first PR here ! :)  This PR close #3000  It might close #1903   #2152 is also about it  however having built from origin/master don't seems to solve the issue    PS : I'm not sure about merging to master. Title: Fix field context conversion from JavaScript to Lua
Body: **Addresses**  Fixes #3199.    **Description**  While Lua support is maintained  the formatting of fields and context has to be converted from JavaScript statements to Lua-friendly ones. Objects `{key: value}` are translated to tables `{key = value}`. If however the colon appears inside the value  it would also get replaced.    The proper way to handle it might be to use a regular expression like: `/(?<=\\w):\\s+(?=[['{\\d\\w-])/g` so that only the colons after the keys are replaced.     The expression would specify a colon preceded by:    - word    followed by a space and:    - `[` : if value is a MFField  - `{`: if value is a Vector2/Vector3/SFNode  - `\\d`: if value is a SFFloat/SFInt  - `'`: if value is a string  - `-` if value is a negative SFFloat/SFInt.  - `\\w` if value is a word (true  false  undefined)    It works  but it almost feels overkill. The workaround of replacing `.replace(":"  " =")` to `.replace(": "  " = ")` works so well that I'm tempted to just leave it like that.    Also  I took the opportunity to clean up how the the context strings are encoded  using `'` for string instead of `"`.

Title: Fix incorrect resetting of Transform
Body: **Description**  As surfaced in #3051  under certain conditions the resetting (from GUI or from supervisor) does not appear to be working.   In some cases the objects don't return to their initial position  in others they do but when the position is queried the value is incorrect.    The issue doesn't not appear to be related to the nested-ness of PROTO files as previously thought  chipping away at the example mentioned in #3036 revealed that the MRE is just having a simple structure like   ```  DEF OUTER_NODE Transform {    children [      DEF INNER_NODE Transform {            }    ]  }  ```    In this case  the objects return to their initial position but after a reset their position values are incorrect. Similar situations to `T { T {} }` that also fail are: `T { S {} }`  `G { T { S { } } }`  `S { T { S { } } }`   and `S { T { T { } } }`    Specifically  what appears to be failing is the following condition:  - pick one of the structures mentioned above  let's call the inner node INNER and the outer OUTER.  - get their position: `positions_A`  - move the OUTER (for example using `set_sf_vec3f`)  - get their positions: `positions_B`    So far so good  the INNER is translated as well.    - reset and get the positions: `position_C`. This should be equal to `positions_A` but **isn't.**  - move the OUTER (for example using `set_sf_vec3f`)  - get their positions: `positions_D`. This should be equal to `position_B` and **it is**.    So the issue really is just the first value after the reset.

Title: Add Contact Points Tracking
Body: Similar to #2279 we want to provide an API function for contact points tracking.    This PR adds the following API functions:  - `wb_supervisor_node_enable_contact_point_tracking(WbNodeRef node  int sampling_period  bool include_descendants)`  - `wb_supervisor_node_disable_contact_point_tracking(WbNodeRef node  bool include_descendants)`  - `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_points(WbNodeRef node  bool include_descendants  int *size)`    The `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_points` function is a substitute for:  - `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_point`  - `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_point_node`  - `wb_supervisor_node_get_number_of_contact_points`    Therefore  these functions are deprecated.    - Tracking    - [x] Basic implementation    - Add support for other languages:      - [x] C++      - [x] Python      - [x] Java      - [x] Matlab      - [x] ROS    - [x] Documentation    - [x] Tests    - [x] ROS tests    - [x] Controller.def + WbLanguage.cpp  - `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_points`    - [x] Basic implementation    - Add support for other languages:      - [x] C++      - [x] Python      - [x] Java      - [x] Matlab      - [x] ROS    - [x] Documentation    - [x] Tests    - [x] ROS tests    - [x] Controller.def + WbLanguage.cpp  - [x] Changelog  - Verify     - [ ] Matlab `wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_points`  - Non related fixes    - [x] Change the ROS sampling_period type for pose tracking    - [x] Fix pose and field tracking reset handling     - [x] Ignore `wb_supervisor_node_set_joint_position`     - [x] Change Python API to return an object instead of dictionary    **Documentation**    https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/supervisor?version=feature-contact-point-tracking#wb_supervisor_node_get_contact_points    **Development Scenario**    ```  #VRML_SIM R2021b utf8  WorldInfo {    basicTimeStep 16    coordinateSystem "NUE"  }  Viewpoint {    orientation 0.2744370696263734 -0.9240498909372512 -0.2661129344352567 4.66421960062771    position 3.2657338363728203 2.5300277265960878 0.4360826908960025  }  TexturedBackground {  }  TexturedBackgroundLight {  }  Floor {  }  WoodenBox {  }  DEF BOX WoodenBox {    translation 0 1.31 0.28    name "wooden box(1)"    mass 1  }  Robot {    controller "contacttracking"    supervisor TRUE  }  ```    ```python  from controller import Supervisor  robot = Supervisor()  use_new_api = True    timestep = int(robot.getBasicTimeStep())  box = robot.getFromDef('BOX')  box.enableContactPointsTracking(timestep)    while robot.step(timestep) != -1:      if use_new_api:          print(box.getContactPoints())      else:          n_points = box.getNumberOfContactPoints()          for i in range(n_points):              print(f'#{i}: {box.getContactPoint(i)}')              print(f'#{i}: {box.getContactPointNode(i)}')  ```    ```java  import com.cyberbotics.webots.controller.Supervisor;  import com.cyberbotics.webots.controller.Node;  import com.cyberbotics.webots.controller.ContactPoint;    public class contacttracking_java {    public static void main(String[] args) {      Supervisor robot = new Supervisor();        int timeStep = (int) Math.round(robot.getBasicTimeStep());        Node box = robot.getFromDef("BOX");            while (robot.step(timeStep) != -1){        ContactPoint[] points = box.getContactPoints(false);        for (int i = 0; i < points.length; i++) {          System.out.println(points[i].getNodeId());          System.out.println(points[i].getPoint()[1]);          }      }    }  }  ```

Title: Fix kinematic simulation triggering a field regeneration which leads to a crash
Body: **Description**  test world: [bug_crash_kinetic_regeneration.zip](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/files/6711975/bug_crash_kinetic_regeneration.zip)    If the world file includes a PROTO  like the following:    ```  #VRML_SIM R2021b utf8    PROTO MyHingeJoint  [    field SFNode                                 jointParameters   NULL    field MFNode                                 device            [ ]    field SFNode                                 endPoint          NULL  ]  {    %{      local a = fields.endPoint.value;    }%    HingeJoint {      jointParameters IS jointParameters      device IS device      endPoint IS endPoint    }  }  ```   where a field is a template regenerator (specifically of type Solid like the `endPoint` of a `HingeJoint`). If this PROTO is used in kinematic mode (i.e the `Solid` lacks a `Physics` node)  when the kinematic `updatePosition` step occurs [here](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/868b331bb7d29cc2ceed96233dd35c2752f1c84a/src/webots/nodes/WbHingeJoint.cpp#L384-L401)  the call of [setTranslationAndRotation](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/868b331bb7d29cc2ceed96233dd35c2752f1c84a/src/webots/nodes/WbHingeJoint.cpp#L397) triggers the emission of a `fieldChange` which in turn provokes a regeneration. In theory  this regeneration would potentially occur at every timestep  but in practice it makes webots crash (probably because the regeneration happens mid-physics step  after `setTranslationAndRotation` a function `resetPhysics` is called which likely references a node that is no longer valid).    During the execution of the simulation step I don't think regenerations should even occur  even less so considering field changes of type `translation`  `rotation` and `position` are excluded [here](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/868b331bb7d29cc2ceed96233dd35c2752f1c84a/src/webots/nodes/utils/WbTemplateManager.cpp#L197-L202).    The reason it bypasses this restriction is because the test of whether it's a `Solid` or not is done on the uppermost regenerable node (which in this case is of type `HingeJoint` hence passes through) instead of the node itself that triggered it.    **Fix**  Essentially there's two ways of fixing it  but I'm not 100% convinced which of the two is best:  - Option 1: proposed solution. Since the field that triggered the regeneration belongs to node `templateNode`  it seems to me more reasonable to use this same node when checking if it is of type `Solid` (and therefore if the field is one of these excluded cases). If regeneration has to occur  then of course what is regenerated has to be the uppermost `templateNode`  - Option 2: find the uppermost `templateNode` that can be regenerated (as it already does) and replace the current condition `dynamic_cast<const WbSolid *>(templateNode)` with  `dynamic_cast<const WbSolid *>(templateNode) || WbNodeUtilities::hasASolidDescendant(templateNode)`    To me option 1 appears to be the more reasonable one and the one less prone to undesired side-effects.

Title: Conversion of Lua PROTO files to JavaScript

When the two PROTO are somewhat similar  the review is fairly easy but  for those where the two versions are significantly different it might be easier to open them in dummy world and play with them to see if something breaks.    For the `WbQjsFile` module  the functions I exposed were the minimal I needed for the conversion. So  I don't know if this module should be more complex than that (or something more generic). Title: Fix endless regeneration resulting in a crash
Body: **Description**  Cases of endless regeneration:  - ~~Addresses #2994 - work in progress~~      - no longer needed  fixed by  #3227.  - The first example #3215 however still appears to be infinitely regenerating.    The smallest reproducible example I could manage for the second issue is this: [bug_mf_deletion.zip](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/files/6717186/bug_mf_deletion.zip)    **Steps to reproduce:**  Open world  delete the second `RoadLine` in the `lines` field. Webots should crash.  Or do the same in a world that has a `AddLaneRoadSegment.proto`    Basically it involves:   - nested PROTO  - template regenerator fields on both levels of the PROTO  - IS statements involving this fields (which needs to be in a `Solid { Group { children [] } }` structure for some reason).    I couldn't simplify it further without loosing the crash  which makes the debugging rather tricky given how specific of a structure it is. However  basically what appears to going on is that:    When removing the the `RoadLine` from the `MFField`  the field `lines` being a template regenerator  triggers a regeneration which propagates to the most internal PROTO first  during this process  after creating the new node  the parameter fields of this newly created node are redirected to the parent parameters [here](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/ecbbc1642d80f3e702bfbbf619d544f85e4ceb06/src/webots/nodes/utils/WbTemplateManager.cpp#L390-L398). In the process of doing this redirection however  the copy of this parameter [here](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/da4f3d4e26be0b5da401547daef7afc4374743f6/src/webots/vrml/WbField.cpp#L325-L326) is not protected against generating new signals which triggers a new regeneration. Because of this  the inner PROTO regenerates infinitely until at some point it crashes webots.    The current implementation fixes the issue and the blocking of the signal occurs only during the regeneration of a node as doing so every time would break several cases in the test suite as this function also plays a role during the building of the node structure.    Despite being reasonable and despite fixing both the MRE case and issue #3215  I definitely would like a second opinion on the approach or possible side-effects.

Title: Fix regeneration of a PROTO boundingObject
Body: **Fixes**  Fixes #3215 - second example.    **Description**  The MRE is a proto such as this:    ```  #VRML_SIM R2021b utf8    PROTO Test [    field SFFloat    height          2       # Defines the height of the pipe.  ]  {    %{ local a = fields.height.value; }%    Group { # set of boxes      children [          Transform {            children [              Box {                size %{= a }% %{= a }% %{= a }%              }            ]          }      ]    }  }  ```   When the user changes a parameter from the interface  it triggers a regeneration because this field is a template regenerator. As this PROTO is used in the `boundingObject`  and its parent is of type `Solid` it enters [this](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/868b331bb7d29cc2ceed96233dd35c2752f1c84a/src/webots/nodes/utils/WbTemplateManager.cpp#L338-L340) condition. However  when it searches for the corresponding node in the parent fields (or rather  it requests its `nodeIndex`)  it does so in the children field instead of the `boundingObject` field hence failing the assertion since it cannot find it there.

Title: Fix a controller crash when changing the controller
Body: Fixes #3231    In addition  this PR solves the Webots crash that can be produced as follows:  - open a world   - pause and reset   - set controller B   - revert to controller A   - run crashes Webots.    ---    After the reset  the running controller (let's call it `A`) is stopped and added to the `mWaitingControllers` list. Once the controller parameter is switched from `A` to `B` the controller `B` is added to the `mWaitingControllers` as well (but the controller `A` is not deleted as it is not in the `mControllers` list). It makes both controllers be executed at the beginning of the simulation and making both of them crash.    This PR deletes the robot's controller from the `mWaitingControllers` and `mNewControllers` lists before adding a new one.    I am not sure whether I am breaking something though.

Title: Drastically reduce package size
Body: Following up #2591  this PR introduces Webots URLs. Webots URLs can be used in a world file to specify textures  meshes  sounds  etc. in a similar way as the https URLs introduced in #2591. Webots URLs come as an alternative to relative or absolute file references and identify a unique file in the Webots package.  A Webots URL has the following form: `webots://` following by a file path relative to `WEBOTS_HOME`.  For example: [webots://projects/samples/geometries/worlds/textures/webots_box.png](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cyberbotics/webots/R2021a/projects/samples/geometries/worlds/textures/water_flow.jpg)    When releasing a new webots package  all world and proto files will be processed and all `webots://` URLs will be replaced with their equivalent `https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cyberbotics/webots/` URL  so that all the resources files (textures  meshes  sounds  etc.) can be omitted from the distributed package. This will significantly reduce the size of the Webots packages.    Released version will use the GitHub tag to refer to resources  e.g.  R2021a  R2021a-rev1  R2021b  etc.  Nightly builds cannot use the GitHub tag for nightly builds because these tags are destroyed after 3 days. So  instead  they should use the commit sha.    - [x] Implement support for `webots://` URLs in Webots (useful only for Webots developers who checked out the webots repo).  - [ ] ~Add a "Download all resources for offline use" menu item (will download all resources in the cache of Webots).~  - [x] Replace the file URLs with `webots://` in all world files.  - [x] Replace the file URLs with `webots://` in all proto files.      The following protos were converted manually as the script failed because of LUA code:      - SimpleBuilding      - PublicToilet      - SimpleTree      The following protos were skipped as the script failed because of LUA code  but no modifications was needed:      - DirectionalPanel      - ProtoMismatchFieldType (tests folder)  - [x] Replace the file URLs also in the webots_ros submodule. See https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros/pull/59  - [x] Replace the file URLs also in the webots_ros2 repo. See https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots_ros2/pull/233  - [x] Replace the file URLs also in the webots-project. See https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots-projects/pull/4  - [x] Change the export of .x3d files to use `webots://` urls when possible.  - [x] Adapt webotsJS to support `webots://`  - [x] Replace the `webots://` of all world and proto files in the distribution.  - [x] Remove the resources files from the distribution.  - [x] Measure the resulting size of the new webots packages: on Windows  the new package is 0.99 GB instead of 1.64 GB.      Other ideas to reduce the package size:    - on Windows  remove the mingw32 binaries.  - remove the offline documentation  replace it with online documentation only.  - remove the e-puck cross-compiler → move it to a different repo.  - use EXTERNPROTO to move proto files outside of the distribution.  - move projects (worlds  protos  controllers) outside of the distribution.

Title: Fix cabinet primaryAppearance
Body: **Description**  Fixes https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/issues/3337.    The MRE of this bug is this PROTO  ```  PROTO Cabinet [    field SFNode   primaryAppearance   PaintedWood {}    # Defines the primary appearance.    field SFNode   secondaryAppearance PaintedWood {}    # Defines the secondary appearance.  ]  {    Solid {      children [        CabinetDrawer{           primaryAppearance IS primaryAppearance           secondaryAppearance IS secondaryAppearance        }        CabinetDoor {           primaryAppearance IS primaryAppearance           secondaryAppearance IS secondaryAppearance        }      ]    }  }  ```  The reason for the bug is that although `CabinetDoor` has a `primaryAppearance` parameter  this is not used anywhere in the body of the PROTO. As such  when removing the default node and attempting to add a new one (in the parent PROTO `Cabinet`)  the candidates must satisfy both the constraints imposed by `CabinerDrawer` (which uses this field) and `CabinetDoor` (which doesn't) and the result is that no node satisfies both.    The simplest solution is to remove this unnecessary field from `CabinetDoor`. No update to the documentation is necessary since this PROTO is hidden.    PS: At some point we should look into the `isAllowedToInsert` function  trying to debug this from the webots side was a nightmare. There has to be a cleaner way of checking node compatibility.

Title: Fix floor distorsion
Body: **Description**  Fixes https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/issues/3331.    Not exactly a fix  but I've noticed that choosing a size of 1000 or less and the issue virtually disappears. For the purpose of this world  even 100 would've largely sufficed.    The problem appears to be only affect `IndexedFaceSets` which are defined as a single quad (or 2 triangles) which are very long. I don't think it's very common to have a single 10 km-sided triangle. The only case I can think of is a 10 km straight `Road`. However after testing one  the issue doesn't show up at all even for a length of 100 km. Roads however are built as 8 triangles though  so even this case doesn't really fit the bill.    I've resized the floor so that the distortion doesn't appear  but I'm not sure whether it's practically useful to investigate it further given how niche a case it appears to be. I've put a `wontfix` label  but feel free to remove it.      https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/124601739-7b357c80-de68-11eb-8b29-66283f444043.mp4

Title: Fix incorrect cleaning of WbLights
Body: **Description**  This issue can make the guided tour crash (https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/issues/3312) but only on niche situations    The only way I was able to reproduce the crash was:  - open guided tour  - switch very quickly from `mantis.wbt` to `e-puck_line_demo.wbt` worlds while attempting to cancel the loading of either  - at some point  it crashes    Although each of these worlds only has one light source  and therefore the global class variable `cLights` should at most be of size 1  doing this process very quickly resulted in having bigger  `cLights` (size 2  3  5  ...). This is because this variable is appended in the `preFinalize` but only cleared if wren was initialized. In practice however this variable should be cleared regardless  if not  like in this situation what can happen is that pointers of previous worlds persist due to it being canceled before being finalized  and when we access this class variable the pointers are no longer valid resulting in the crash.

Title: Fix error in Lidar RangeFinder measurement when hitting an edge
Body: **Description**  When hitting an edge  the Lidar / RangeFinder was returning values between the two possible values. This was because the values were sampled slightly in-between pixels of the camera.  This is solved by fetching the pixels directly by index instead of coordinates. We multiply the coordinates by the resolution  round it and we get the correct index.    **Related Issues**  This pull-request fixes issue #2736    ![lidar](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/38250944/123385239-9fa27680-d595-11eb-8529-85547f9ce8c0.png)

Title: Fix relocation of Skins
Body: **Description**  Fixes https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/issues/3292    Based on what I understood  `copyExternalProject` comes [into play](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/8eeccb12a698624634b877da7d0d0c0c4e1df5f9/src/webots/editor/WbProjectRelocationDialog.cpp#L211-L212) only if `mExternalProjectPath` is defined  hence if [this](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/8eeccb12a698624634b877da7d0d0c0c4e1df5f9/src/webots/editor/WbProjectRelocationDialog.cpp#L446-L454) point is reached. This is the case only if the skins folder would be inside the `protos` folder but according to `WbSkin`  the skins folder must be at the [root](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/8eeccb12a698624634b877da7d0d0c0c4e1df5f9/src/webots/nodes/WbSkin.cpp#L405) (same level as worlds) hence it will never be the case.  As such  unless I misunderstood  it's sufficient to relocate this skins folder only in `copyProject` and not in `copyExternalProject`.

Title: solve thread hanging after webots process finishes
Body: **Description**  This pull request address a bug that happens in the line https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/eca5ec4ce5774d175a75601a9ff396d4cb633a94/resources/web/server/simulation_server.py#L310 of the simulation server script.    *Bug behavior*: the thread that run webots hang after the user disconnect and the webots process is terminated. Because of that there exists proccesses using the server's memory (can be checked using htop - multiple processes appears linked to the simulation_server.py script) that leads to slow down and problems with the simulation server overtime.    *Solution proposed*: Check if the webots process in terminated in the blocking 'for' loop. If the webots process is None (meaning that the user disconnected and the webots process was terminated or killed) the loop breaks and the thread is completed.    **Related Issues**  This pull-request fixes issue #3400    **Tasks**  No task addressed.    **Documentation**  No need for change in the documentation.    **Screenshots**  No need for screenshots.    **Additional context**  Add any other context about the pull-request here.

Title: Fix pen evaporation
Body: **Description**  Fixes https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/issues/3411.    Although the ink density is a floating point value in the API  the value was cast into an `unsigned char` when sending it to webots. For small values of the random seed  the first value of `rand()` was consistently very small which resulted in it being approximated to zero. On Webots side  there was no check to verify if a division by zero was occurring  hence this first segment of the trail was actually a NaN so it persisted despite the evaporation.    Mac:  ![pen](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/125621620-c651f4f9-3377-43e5-bb7a-51d29cfb2442.png)    Windows:  ![pen_1](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44834743/125621937-7594a44a-6f0e-4cfc-8a40-6e2082d70426.png)

Title: ros default controller based sleep on WallTime instead of simulated time
Body: **Description**  The `ros` default controller uses rate control in its `Ros::run()` function. But the rate control is based on a `ros::Rate` instance  which breaks when using simulated time  hence when providing following arguments to the controller:   ```bash  --synchronize  --clock  ```  The [line 469 of file Ros.cpp](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/c5637734a664733a585219c178eb753c0ff8f37b/projects/default/controllers/ros/Ros.cpp#L469) was modified to ensure WallTime is used in any case. Failing to use WallTime when enabling simulation time does not allow the sleep function to terminate.

Title: LIDAR point cloud generation optimisation
Body:
**Description** After having pinpointed by @lukicdarkoo in https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/issues/3476 The `WbLidar::updatePointCloud` method is probably the biggest bottleneck (by far) in the LiDAR implementation: https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/c5637734a664733a585219c178eb753c0ff8f37b/src/webots/nodes/WbLidar.cpp#L354-L381 **Details** The optimization is made using three way : 1) Factorize code that could be to avoid re-computations. In particular find a way to move the condition like `if (mIsActuallyRotating)` outside the loop. 2) Use increment instead of multiplication : replace values of the form (expression) + (counter) * (increment). We initialize the variable to an initial one and then add at each loop a fixed amount. 3) Replace cos() and sin() usage by an iterative method : Considering that we are taking cos and sin of angle that are only incremented by a fixed amount we could use addition law on cos and sin as : cos(x+dx) = cos(x)cos(dx)-sin(x)sin(dx) sin(x+dx) = sin(x)cos(dx)+cos(x)sin(dx) with x is the previous value angle and dx the angle increment. this way we could compute the next cos/sin that will be used on the next loop using the current values and the cos/sin of the increment which is actually fixed as well. Thus cos and sin computation is only 2 multiplication and 1 addition each. **Results** First I've checked as I could so I hope I've didn't introduce bugs or miscalculations. Also the way I compute variable (iterative way) could introduce some numerical error but using `double` should be enough. Execution speed is obtained by using the Time_uclock function which will obviously be removed before merging. We record the number of us per function call and also the number of ns per points computed. Result should be compared using the branch origin/enhancement-optimize-lidar-point-cloud-initial which include the original code and add those timing things. Maybe Webots use to do those profiling but I found to be the most straight forward way let me know if their are "official stuff for that. Here is what I end up with : here are the ns per points over about 100. ¬† | initial | optimized -- | -- | -- min | 14.14 | 2.31 max | 21.74 | 2.88 average | 18.85 | 2.47 The way 1) give minor improvement but enable 2) which made the timing drop from 20ns to 15ns and most important enable 3) which bring time from 15ns to about 2ns. So about 7.5 times faster :) **Setup**
World

Controller

Title: Add note about coupled motor usage in differentials
Body: Mechanical differentials drive  as described in https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_(mechanical_device) could be very easily simulated using coupled motor. As I just figured out  even if the main role of it is to change speed to avoid slip  it also ensure that each wheel receive the **same** torque (so  for a regular car  each 2 (lets say front) wheel receive half the motor torque). That fact is often overlooked  seen as a drawback for many application (if a wheel slip  the other stop  cause no torque)  but for simulation it actually awesome !  Been trying it on my project with a 4*4 configuration  and work really fine !    This is why that fact could be added in the doc.  However I do feel that my explanation is not very clear  English not been my mother-thong... feel free to update !

Title: Fix matrix to quaternion conversion

For example  if Webots is compiled in the debug mode  the following world will crash Webots after pressing Alt+1 (top view): ``` #VRML_SIM R2021b utf8 WorldInfo { } Viewpoint {   orientation 0 1 0 1.5707996938995747   position 0 0 6 } ``` with error: ``` webots-bin: maths/WbRotation.cpp:24: void WbRotation::fromQuaternion(const WbQuaternion&): Assertion `std::abs(sqrt(q.x() * q.x() + q.y() * q.y() + q.z() * q.z() + q.w() * q.w()) - 1) < 0.0000000001' failed. ./webots: line 90: 121749 Aborted                 (core dumped) "$webots_home/bin/webots-bin" "$@" ```  It doesn't happen with the released version though  the compiler manages to handle it somehow. However  it might cause some unwanted side-effects.

Title: Save with Linux line endings on Windows
Body: When exporting a wrl or x3d file on Windows  the resulting file is different from the same file exported on Linux or macOS. This is due to the use of `QTextStream` class which is converting the text by adding the Windows line endings `\r\n`.    I believe it's better to have the exact same exported files on Windows and Linux / macOS so that the diff is readable.    Unfortunately  it seems there is no way to configure `QTextStream` to produce Linux line endings on Windows  see: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38777334/choose-custom-line-ending-for-text-file-writing-by-qt    So  this PR gets rid of the `QTextStream` class for writing files  so that no Windows specific line ending is written to the exported files.    It also fixes a couple of details in the X3D export.    The PR also replaces some quads by triangles in `Nao.proto` and `VehicleWheel.proto`.    Finally  it also fixes the web_component_studio script to work on Windows and generate files with Linux line endings.    **Note**: X3D exported files sometimes differ on Windows from Linux. This is due to the tesselator algorithm (gluNewTess) which behaves differently on Windows and Linux: The (1  2  3  4) quad may be tesselated as (4 2 3) + (2 4 1) on Windows and as (1 3 4) + (3 1 2) on Linux. Both are correct  but differ... Hence the coordIndex values may be different on Windows and Linux. Another source of difference is that the WREN matrices (from `wr_transform_get_matrix`) slightly differ due to the accumulation of small differences in trigonometric functions and when we export the bounding objects of a Solid node as an IndexedLineSet  we rely on WREN to generate the coordinates of this line set. Hence  the values of the coordinates sometimes slightly differ between Windows and Linux.

Title: Virtual RoboCup Humanoid 2021
Body: I will continue the development of the referee on this branch  which is more convenient to run the tests. Once everything works  we could merge it to the Webots repository.    ### List of the bugs appearing through automated testing  - [x] Time management has to be updated    - Currently not guaranteeing that each step is not faster than...    - Real time waited is longer if the simulator can't match the real_time_factor in average  - [ ] Scoring goals from the different kind of Game Interruptions    - See all 'scoring' scenarios in 'game_interruptions'  - [x] Scoring goals from KickOff    - See 'game_phases/kick_off/'  scenarios 2 and 4  - [x] Penalty when opponent enters center circle while ball is not in play    - See 'game_phases/kick_off/'  scenarios 1 and 2  - [x] Dropped ball not implemented    - See 'game_phases/dropped_ball'  - [x] Illegally positioned robots are not penalized in SET after a goal    - See 'game_phases/repositioning'  - [ ] Problem on the INITIAL duration of the second half-time    - After 17 real-time seconds state has not changed (real_time factor 0.1)  see above    - Tested separately  even 30 minutes of simulated time after (5 minutes real-time)  state still hasn't changed (with default world)    - This problem impacts 'game_phases/second_half'  'results/win' and  'results/draw'  - [x] Robots staying out of the turf for more than 20 seconds are not penalized    - See 'misc_fouls/leaving_field'  - [ ] Inactive goalies are not penalized    - See 'misc_fouls/inactive_goalie'  - [x] Robot falling partially on the opponent side in the SET phase is not penalized    - See 'positioning/ready' (and issue 26)  - [ ] Robots might receive a penalty for being outside of the field during SET after the Autoref sent a PLAYING message to the GameController which leads to robots being sometime penalized at the start of PLAYING.    - This one is a little bit tricky because it might involve the order in which actions are applied in the GameController side.    - See 'positioning/initial' (it has been updated for clarifying the bug)    ### List of the bugs appearing through manual testing  - [ ] Transition to PLAYING from SET is sometimes failing after a goal or after 1st half  - [ ] For penalty shootouts:    - Ball is placed on the center circle  not on the penalty mark    - The transition between the states is not always working automatically    - End of the game is not detected

Title: Add exception handling in publish_release py script
Body: Publishing a nightly build failed (https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/runs/3071646906?check_suite_focus=true) with this error message:  ```    Creating release "Webots Nightly Build (14-7-2021)" with tag "nightly_14_7_2021" on commit "5569ee04f8b281e6f8077883657717f4e396f9f7"  Traceback (most recent call last):    File "scripts/packaging/publish_release.py"  line 103  in <module>      prerelease=True)    File "/usr/local/lib/python3.6/dist-packages/github/Repository.py"  line 1009  in create_git_tag_and_release      target_commitish=object     File "/usr/local/lib/python3.6/dist-packages/github/Repository.py"  line 1061  in create_git_release      "POST"  f"{self.url}/releases"  input=post_parameters    File "/usr/local/lib/python3.6/dist-packages/github/Requester.py"  line 355  in requestJsonAndCheck      verb  url  parameters  headers  input  self.__customConnection(url)    File "/usr/local/lib/python3.6/dist-packages/github/Requester.py"  line 378  in __check      raise self.__createException(status  responseHeaders  output)  github.GithubException.GithubException: 422 {"message": "Validation Failed"  "errors": [{"resource": "Release"  "code": "already_exists"  "field": "tag_name"}]  "documentation_url": "https://docs.github.com/rest/reference/repos#create-a-release"}  Error: Process completed with exit code 1.  ```    The script already checks if a release already exists but in this particular case it was not sufficient.  Handling the exceptions raised when creating the tag and release we should be able to bypass this kind of errors and still upload the packages if the release effectively exists.

For all the other nodes we have to retrieve the descendant nodes:    Nodes overriding the function to retrieve closes descendant nodes with dedicated Wren node:  |Node | Function Overridden | Comments |  | ------ | --------- | -------- |  | BasicJoint | x  | |  | Billboard | x | |  | Geometry | x | |  | Group | x | |  | Motor | x | |  | Muscle  | x | Users can override the visibility properties in the main view switching the `Muscle.isVisible` flag |  | Propeller | x | Webots code overrides the visibility properties when enabling/disabling the slow/fast helix or is the fast helix is selected from the scene tree |  | Shape | x | |  | Slot | x | |  | SolidReference | x | |  | Transform | x | |  | Background | | This function cannot be used to hide background from cameras |   | Fog | | This function cannot be used to hide fog from cameras |    Nodes that doesn't have any associated Wren nodes:  Appearance  Background  Brake  Color  ContactProperties  Coordinate  Damping  Focus  Fog  ImageTexture  ImmersionProperties  JointParameters  Lens  LensFlare  Light  Material  Normal  PBRAppearance  Physics  Recognition  TextureCoordinate  TextureTransform  Viewpoint  WorldInfo  Zoom    Remaining nodes are derived from other nodes already listed.

Title: Robocup controllers
Body: This PR aims at creating webots Robocup controllers for players that will run a TCP/IP server  send and receive protobuf3 messages to/from the actual robot controllers running a remote machine.  The amount of data sent is limited to 100 MB/s per team  computed on a time window of 1 second.  Data packets over this quota will be dropped.    - [x] Add protobuf3 dependency on Windows  Linux and macOS.  - [x] Implement protobuf3 messaging with a sample client program.  - [x] Fix proto tests that were conflicting with `.proto` protobuf files.  - [x] Implement the quota system.  - [x] Reject controller connections from non-authorized hosts.  - [x] Add a basic referee that setups the game from json files  including field size.  - [x] Referee automatically launches GameController.  - [x] Referee send clock messages to GameController.     The protobuf3 [messages](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cyberbotics/webots/feature-robocup-controllers/projects/samples/contests/robocup/controllers/player/messages.proto) should be sent/received over a socket connection to the simulation machine on a port corresponding to each player.

Title: Feature enu geometries
Body: **Description**  Convert the geometries to be z-aligned    **Tasks**  Add the list of tasks of this PR.    - [x] Convert cylinder    - [x] Convert capsule    - [x] Convert cone    - [x] Convert plane    - [x] Convert elevation grid    - [x] Change doc    - [x] Verify webotsJS (if you want to test it  you have to compile wren with Emscripten and change index.html and WebStreaming.js to point to the local files)    - [x] Adapt the tests      **Additional detail**    There is a script that can convert automatically worlds (scripts/converter/convert_geometries.py).  But it has some known limitations:    - It cannot convert protos  - If there is a DEF geometry that is use in a bounding object and there is already a transform in the bounding object  we need to convert it manually. Because the script add an additional transform to the geometry and become the DEF node  so we would have two Transform in the bounding object  which is forbiden.  - You need to convert by hand the following parameters of ElevationGrid:    -  zDimension -> yDimension    -  zSpacing -> ySpacing    - Add a translation on the upper transform of value -(yDimension -1) * ySpacing either on the negative y (if ENU) or positive z (NUE)    - Inverse the lines of the height     - Rotation the elevation grid by (1 0 0 -1.57)  - If a plane is scaled by a transform  you have to invert y and z scale. You also need to rotate it by (1 0 0 -1.57) (even if it does not have a scale)  - Sometimes the resulting rotation is weird when squashing transforms

Body: Improve the conversion scripts and begin converting basic PROTOs (PROTOs that don't contain other PROTOs)    **Tasks**  - Script improvements    - [x] Convert `cord` in `Geometry`    - [x] Detect whether a PROTO contains a JavaScript fragment    - [x] Fix array parsing issues    - [x] Comment handling   - PROTOs    - [x] Kinect    - [x] Floor    - [x] MultiSenseS21    - [x] DelphiESR    - [x] RobotisLds01.proto    - [x] HokuyoUrg04lx.proto    - [x] HokuyoUtm30lx.proto    - [x] HokuyoUrg04lxug01.proto    - [x] MultiSenseS21.proto    - [x] Servo.proto    - [x] IbeoLux.proto    - [x] SmsUmrr-0a29.proto    - [x] SmsUmrr-0a31.proto    - [x] SmsUmrr-0a30.proto    - [x] SmsUmrrShape.proto    - [x] SharpGP2Y0A41SK0F.proto    - [x] SharpGP2Y0A02YK0F.proto    - [x] SharpGP2D120.proto    - [x] SharpGP2Y0A710K0F.proto    - [x] DelphiESR.proto    - [x] JetsonNano.proto    - [x] SickLdMrs.proto    - [x] SickS300.proto    - [x] SickLms291.proto    - [x] Robotiq3fGripper.proto    - [x] Kinect.proto    - [x] VelodynePuck.proto    - [x] VelodyneHDL-64E.proto    - [x] VelodyneHDL-32E.proto    - [x] VelodyneVLP-16.proto    **Robotiq**  After running the [`robotiq`](https://github.com/ros-industrial/robotiq) description we get the following:  ![Screenshot-20210824161302-836x402](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2135826/130632472-2bf9ebe2-967c-44c3-ba3f-ecdda511e5be.png)    The root frame (`palm`) is the same as Webots PROTO frame. In addition  there is a child frame (`tool0`) that has X-forward. However  since we only care about the root frame I haven't changed anything  the PROTO corresponds to the URDF description.    ---    Accidentally converted:  - (053) objects/buildings/protos/BungalowStyleHouse.proto  - (054) objects/buildings/protos/HouseWithGarage.proto

Title: Avoid changing the LD_LIBRARY_PATH environment in the bashrc
Body: It makes other packages crash. For example  RViz loads the Webots Qt library instead of the system Qt library. A developer should be responsible for configuring the `LD_LIBRARY_PATH` environment variable.

Title: Measure of the impact of adding a Transform node
Body: To estimate the impact of a tranform node  we lead multiple tests. The simulation is an item falling from a height of 3m until it hits a ball. It purposes to encounters bounding boxes. This simulation is repeated multiple times. The results are the average simulation time. We change the orientation of the vehicle using a transform node  so the first experiment is to measure the simulation time of this simulation for a world in NUE  (master/2021b version) and the same world but in ENU  (#3658 / 2021c version). As you can see bellow  these results are not relevant to show the impact of adding this node:     ## Simulation time between an item with and without an extra Tranform node    ### Toyota  2 extra transform    - 2021b:   average on 1000 sim with ball on [0.9;0.6] 724.588ms    - 2021c:   average on 1000 sim with ball on [0.9;0.6] 726ms    - Difference:  difference on 1000 sim: 1.412ms  *loss in performance: 0.19%*    ### Citroen  3 extra transform  - 2021b:   average on 1000 sim with ball on [0.9;0.6] 722ms   average on 10000 sim with ball on [0.9;0.6] 722ms   average on 1000 sim with ball on [0;0.6]: 743.932ms ; with tesla bounding box: 747.128ms        - 2021c:   average on 1000 sim with ball on [0.9;0.6] 735.584ms    average on 10000 sim with ball on [0.9;0.6] 735.602ms   average on 1000 sim with ball on [0;0.6]: 742.02ms ; with tesla bounding box: 745.652ms    - Difference:  difference on 1000 sim with ball on [0.9;0.6]: 13.584ms  difference on 10000 sim with ball on [0.9;0.6]: 13.602ms  difference with ball on [0 0 0.6]: 1.9ms    **CCL: the location of the ball affects the simulation time.  loss in performance with ball on [0.9;0.6] : 1.85%**    ### Tesla  1 extra transform    - 2021b:   average on 1000 simulations 724.92ms   average on 10000 simulations 724.9036ms   average on 1000 sim with ball on [0 0 0.6]: 723.988ms     - 2021c:   average on 1000 simulations 725.148ms   average on 10000 simulations 725.2032ms   average on 1000 sim with ball on [0 0 0.6]: 723.988ms    - Difference:  difference on 1000 sim: 0.228ms  difference on 10000 sim: 0.2996ms  **loss in performance: 0.04%**    ### OfficePhone  no transform    - 2021b:  average on 1000 simulations: 1.407116s    - 2021c:  average on 1000 simulations: 1.0715720000000002s    ### Conclusion of the first experiment    Even if using the same world  controller and by only changing the protos orientation the results are not satisfying. For example  we observe a difference with the OfficePhone object which has no transform. We can conclude that the different version or the orientation of the protos affect the simulation time. And in general the performance of the version 2021c on this simulation is slightly slower.  The second experiment is to measure the performance by changing the number of transform node for the same proto on the same version 2021c.    ## Simulation time between an item with one and with multiple extra Transform nodes    ### Citroen    - 9 extra transform for 10000 simulations: 720ms and 720ms. no difference  - 55 extra transform: 742.104ms  - 109 extra transform: 742.104ms  - 109 different extra transform (32 rdm translations): for 1000 sim: 742.104ms for 10000 sim: 742.0484ms    **Difference: 22.104ms  loss in performance for 55 or 109 extra transform: 2.98%  estimate loss in performance for 1 extra transform: [0;0.05]%**    ### Tesla    - 9 extra transform for 10000 simulations: 0.712s and 0.712s   no difference    ## Conclusion    We can observe that adding extra transform nodes affects the performance  but it needs a lot of extra transform nodes (>50) to be visible  and so it seems that adding a few Transform nodes does not affect the performance for the performed simulation. We could then saving a lot of time by only rotating the whole proto to FLU  simplify the review and prevent mistakes of changing the meshes one by one.

Title: Attempt to fix Window CI build
Body: It seems the openjdk chocolatey package was silently upgraded from version 16 to version 17 without notice. Hence the openjdk-16.0.2 folder was not existing any more  and that broke our build process. Since the openjdk16 package doesn't exist  I upgraded to openjdk17 with the hope it will be more stable than the plain openjdk package which may be upgraded again in the future to version 18 or so. I also updated the [wiki](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/wiki/Windows-Optional-Dependencies/_compare/65c2be9769423f9cd7325b4a212cd6f4f4f8f617).

Title: FLU Implement backward compatibility mechanism
Body:
To avoid breaking worlds and PROTOs we add a mechanism to handle the backward compatibility by adding Transform nodes and rotation Transform descendants. **Tasks** - [x] Proof of concept - Cases - [x] 21b PROTO inside 21b PROTO - [x] 21c PROTO inside 21b PROTO - [x] 21b PROTO inside 21c PROTO - [x] Primitive inside 21b PROTO - [x] Primitive inside 21b world - Cover all nodes - [x] Cylinder - [x] Capsule - [x] Cone - [x] Plane - [x] Elevation grid - [x] Camera - [x] Range Finder - [x] Lidar - [x] Radar - [x] Track - [x] Viewpoint - [x] TouchSensor - [x] Connector - [x] Emitter & Receiver - [x] Pen - [x] Fix reset - [x] Handle USE/DEF - [x] Add tests World example ``` #VRML_SIM R2021c utf8 WorldInfo { } Viewpoint { orientation 0.1763811647303118 -0.3150091039421665 -0.9325550649489456 5.201713829247902 position -0.3639376985270853 -1.5105649727458803 1.0602391552040498 } TexturedBackground { } TexturedBackgroundLight { } Floor { size 100 100 } Robot { translation -2.69 0 0 children [ Camera { children [ DEF BOX_SHAPE Shape { geometry Box { size 0.1 0.1 0.1 } } ] boundingObject USE BOX_SHAPE } ] } TrashContainer { } JetBot { } UR3e { translation 0 0.33 1.54865e-06 rotation 1 0 0 4.692820414042842e-06 } DEF TEST Spot { translation 1.02 0.624 0.6 rotation 1 0 0 1.5708 } ```

Title: Fix Laser intersecting transparent objects 3468
Body: This pull-request fixes issue #3468  The change make Laser Distance sensor ignore transparent objects (Bounding Box).    What was done:     * Added a isTransparent const function to the WbGeometry class.  * Added check ignore transparent objects in WbDistanceSensor::rayCollisionCallback when in Laser mode.    I think that the documentation section here should also be changed to reflect the new behavior.  https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/distancesensor?version=develop#distancesensor-types    Like adding a new line in the table describing the behavior.  Ignore Transparent Objects | No | No | No | Yes    Warning:   You need to have the transparency set to 1.0 on the BoundingBox and the Child object to have the proper behavior.  Having only one of them set can lead to unnatural effects.    Extension to other Distance Sensors?  I guess the behavior for the other modes really depends on the interpretation of the Transparent flag here.  If it is defining an object as being glass for example  then Sonar and Infra-Red are likely able to detect that.    If it is air then it should probably be handled differently since other objects are likely able to bump into it.

Title: Fix crash in Highway_overtake wbt 3556 due to acos getting out of va
Body: Fix crash in Highway_overtake.wbt #3556 due to acos getting out of valid range value causing a NaN valid to be generated.    This in turn is assigned to a WbRotation angle which triggers an infinite notification loop leading to a stack overflow.  A equality check with a NaN value always being false  the WbSFRotation keeps on emitting changed signals.    Add WbMathsUtilities::clampedAcos and replace acos calls with that when the code in place was not already checking the bounds.  Add WbMathsUtilities::clampedAsin too  and update code using asin to prevent  indefinite values being generated.    WbRotation::isValid has been updated to check against NaN value stored in the angle part too.    Both clampedAcos and clampedAsin functions are inline for performance reasons.

Title: Add error message on connection timeout
Body: **Description**  When the simulation server is offline  we noticed that we don't get any errors message.    I fixed this issue in `server.js`  but I'm not sure if we should call `this._view.onquit()`  since it's also not called when the response from the session server starts with `Error:`: https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/blob/53b60081c13e3b3f9dfee31fa4046c45dc870219/resources/web/wwi/Server.js#L31    What's your opinion on that @BenjaminDeleze ?

Title: Fix acos issues
Body: Following the previous comments on issue  [#3556](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/issues/3556)  I updated the previously added code with an assert if the input value is way out of range.  Here "way out of range" means greater by 0.0001.  I tested the highway_overtake in debug and it still works so the errors were always smaller than the epsilon specified.

Title: Fix cppcheck2 6 errors
Body: It seems a new version of ccpcheck landed on the macOS CI machine  breaking the source tests there.  This PR attempts at fixing the code to be compliant with this new version of cppcheck.    It seems there are a few falses positive which I silenced by `cppcheck-suppress` statements.  The `cppcheck-suppress virtualCallInConstructor` are somehow false positive resulting from calls to `QtObject::connect` in constructors. This apparently safe to silence them as the corresponding methods are not called from the constructor  see https://stackoverflow.com/questions/53527950/is-it-safe-to-connect-a-signal-to-a-pure-virtual-slot-in-a-constructor-of-a-base

Title: Add a function to get a Speed Vector from a GPS
Body: Add new wb_gps_get_speed_vector function to the GPS to retrieve the motion delta between the sampling points.    This pull-request fixes issue [#3660](https://github.com/cyberbotics/webots/issues/3660)      - Add wb_gps_get_speed_vector and wired it to WbGPS and other parts.    - Update documentation    - Update gps device sample code to show how to get the new values.    **Documentation**  This PR updates the GPS page https://cyberbotics.com/doc/reference/gps?version=develop#gps    I hope that I got all the parts that needs to be wired.  I wasn't sure about the Matlab part. I left the function commented like the get_value ones. Not sure why it is that way in the first place but I figured that any function returning a pointer being commented the new one should be too.    Let me know if I forgot anything  quite probable.
